isodes6         = 22\n| start6            = {{Start date|2013|9|26}}\n| startrating6      = 3.27<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/09/27/thursday-final-ratings-the-big-bang-theory-the-michael-j-fox-show-the-crazy-ones-adjusted-down/205200/|title=Thursday Final Ratings: 'The Big Bang Theory', 'The Michael J Fox Show' & 'The X Factor' Adjusted Up; 'The Crazy Ones' Adjusted Down|work=TV by the Numbers|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|date=September 27, 2013|accessdate=September 28, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016182345/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/09/27/thursday-final-ratings-the-big-bang-theory-the-michael-j-fox-show-the-crazy-ones-adjusted-down/205200/|archive-date=October 16, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| end6              = {{End date|2014|4|24}}\n| endrating6        = 2.71<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/04/25/thursday-final-ratings-the-big-bang-theory-the-millers-adjusted-down/257405/|title=Thursday Final Ratings: 'The Big Bang Theory' & 'The Vampire Diaries' Adjusted Up; 'The Millers' Adjusted Down|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|work=TV by the Numbers|date=April 25, 2014|accessdate=April 25, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426201940/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/04/25/thursday-final-ratings-the-big-bang-theory-the-millers-adjusted-down/257405/|archive-date=April 26, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| season6           = 2013\u201314\n| rank6             = 115<ref name=\"tvbyseason6\">{{cite web|last=Deadline Team|first=The|title=Full 2013-14 Series Rankings|url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/05/tv-season-series-rankings-2013-full-list-2/|accessdate=May 23, 2014|date=May 23, 2014|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6PpJWyOpl?url=http://www.deadline.com/2014/05/tv-season-series-rankings-2013-full-list-2/|archive-date=May 25, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| viewers6          = 3.76<ref name=\"tvbyseason6\" />\n\n| link7             = Parks and Recreation (season 7)\n| timeslot7         = Tuesday 8:00 pm, 8:30 pm\n| episodes7         = 13\n| start7            = {{Start date|2015|1|13}}\n| startrating7      = 3.75<ref name=\"Episodes 1 and 2\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/01/15/tuesday-final-ratings-person-of-interest-ncis-new-orleans-adjusted-up/350211/|title=Tuesday Final Ratings: 'Person of Interest' & 'NCIS: New Orleans' Adjusted Up|work=TV by the Numbers|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|date=January 15, 2015|accessdate=January 15, 2015|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6a7o8qXLX?url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/01/15/tuesday-final-ratings-person-of-interest-ncis-new-orleans-adjusted-up/350211/|archive-date=July 18, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| end7              = {{End date|2015|2|24}}\n| endrating7        = 4.15<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/02/25/tuesday-final-ratings-the-voice-adjusted-up-ncis-ncis-new-orleans-fresh-off-the-boat-new-girl-tvs-hottest-commercials-adjusted-down/367490/|title=Tuesday Final Ratings: 'The Voice' Adjusted Up; 'NCIS', 'NCIS: New Orleans', 'Fresh of the Boat', 'New Girl' & 'TV's Hottest Commercials' Adjusted Down|work=TV by the Numbers|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|date=February 25, 2015|accessdate=February 25, 2015|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6a7oJPyJZ?url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/02/25/tuesday-final-ratings-the-voice-adjusted-up-ncis-ncis-new-orleans-fresh-off-the-boat-new-girl-tvs-hottest-commercials-adjusted-down/367490/|archive-date=July 18, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| season7           = 2014\u201315\n| rank7             = 119<ref name=\"Entertainment2015\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/05/2014-15-full-tv-season-ratings-shows-rankings-1201431167/ |title=Full 2014\u201315 Series Rankings |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=May 22, 2015 |accessdate=May 22, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6YifxgqG8?url=http://deadline.com/2015/05/2014-15-full-tv-season-ratings-shows-rankings-1201431167/ |archivedate=May 22, 2015 |df=}}</ref>\n| viewers7          = 4.57<ref name=\"Entertainment2015\"/>\n}}\n\n{{Quote box |salign=right |width=240px |align=right | quote = I would love it if our ratings went up and up, and we've done a pretty good job of making our show inviting and friendly, welcoming to new viewers. Other than that, I'm not sure what else we can do. It's very disconcerting. | source =\u2013 [[Michael Schur]]<ref name=\"Heisler0324\" />}}\n\n''Parks and Recreation'' struggled in the [[Nielsen ratings]] throughout its entire run on NBC.<ref name=\"Heisler0324\" /> The series premiere was seen by 6.77&nbsp;million viewers,<ref name=\"PilotRating\"/> which media outlets described as a strong opening, comparable to the average [[Nielsen ratings]] for ''[[30 Rock]]'', another Thursday-night show on NBC.<ref name=\"PilotRating\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Ryan |first=Joal |title=Parks and Rec's Solid Approval Rating |publisher=[[E!]] |date=April 10, 2009 |url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/b118103_parks_recs_solid_approval_rating.html |accessdate=April 11, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5uFU5iQEB?url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/b118103_parks_recs_solid_approval_rating.html |archivedate=November 15, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref> Viewership declined almost every week over the rest of the season,<ref name=\"Martin1118\"/> culminating in a season low of 4.25&nbsp;million viewers for the final episode.<ref name=\"RockShowRating\"/> ''Parks and Recreation'' ended the first season with an overall average rating of 5.97&nbsp;million viewers, ranking 94th in a list of 193 network shows for the [[2008\u201309 United States network television schedule|2008\u201309 television season]].<ref name=\"0809ratings\">{{cite web|title=ABC Medianet |publisher=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=May 27, 2009 |url=http://www.abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=052709_07 |accessdate=June 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5iwEcAyP4?url=http://www.abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=052709_07 |archivedate=August 11, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref> ''The Office'' experienced similarly poor ratings during its first season and later became a success. Low viewership presented a greater challenge for ''Parks and Recreation'' because NBC now trailed [[CBS]], [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] and [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] in the ratings, and the move of comedian [[Jay Leno]] from ''[[The Tonight Show]]'' to [[The Jay Leno Show|a variety show]] in NBC's 10:00&nbsp;pm weeknight slot left less room on the network's primetime schedule.<ref name=\"NYT0326\" /> At the end of the season, members of the cast and crew were stressed because they did not know whether the show would be renewed.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dunn |first=Valeree |title=Performer Spotlight on ... Retta |work=The UIS Journal |date=October 14, 2009 |url=http://www.uis.edu/journal/artsEntertainment/2009/20091014spotlightonretta.html |accessdate=April 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5yBlCXaLK?url=http://www.uis.edu/journal/artsEntertainment/2009/20091014spotlightonretta.html |archivedate=April 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Adalian |first=Josef |title=The Vulture Transcript: ''Parks and Rec''s Chris Pratt on the Surprise Andy-April Wedding, With Bonus Revelations About His Co-stars |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=April 21, 2011 |url=https://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2011/04/chris_pratt_parks_and_recreati.html |accessdate=April 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5yBlGpjVn?url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2011/04/chris_pratt_parks_and_recreati.html |archivedate=April 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref>\n\nAlthough ''Parks and Recreation'' achieved critical success during the second season, the show continued to suffer in the ratings.<ref name=\"Weiner1202\" /> By December 2009, the average episode viewership was 5.3&nbsp;million viewers, which was lower than the average ratings for other Thursday-night NBC comedy shows like ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]''{{'}}s 6.5&nbsp;million viewers, ''[[30 Rock]]''{{'}}s 7.3&nbsp;million and ''The Office''{{'}}s 10.1&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"Weiner1202\" /> For the overall second season, ''Parks and Recreation'' had an overall average viewership of 4.6&nbsp;million viewers, making it the 108th ranked network series for the [[2009\u201310 United States network television schedule|2009\u201310 season]].<ref name=\"0910ratings\">{{cite news|last=Gorman |first=Bill |title=Final 2009\u201310 Broadcast Primetime Show Average Viewership |publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]] |date=June 16, 2010 |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2010/06/16/final-2009-10-broadcast-primetime-show-average-viewership/54336/ |accessdate=June 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zZX7grKg?url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2010/06/16/final-2009-10-broadcast-primetime-show-average-viewership/54336/ |archivedate=June 20, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref> The poor ratings continued into the third season, which ended with an overall average rating of 5.1&nbsp;million viewers, the 116th ranked network series of the [[2010\u201311 United States network television schedule|2010\u201311 television season]].<ref name=\"1011ratings\">{{cite news|last=Gorman |first=Bill |title=2010\u201311 Season Broadcast Primetime Show Viewership Averages |publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]] |date=June 1, 2011 |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/06/01/2010-11-season-broadcast-primetime-show-viewership-averages/94407/ |accessdate=June 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zZXRcj1U?url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/06/01/2010-11-season-broadcast-primetime-show-viewership-averages/94407/ |archivedate=June 20, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref> Michael Schur partially attributed the continually low viewership to a decline in ratings for NBC in general, as well as changing viewer trends due to a large number of available channels.<ref name=\"Heisler0324\" />\n\nDespite the generally low ratings, ''Parks and Recreation'' was renewed for a sixth season on May 9, 2013.<ref>[http://www.ismyshowcancelled.com/article/2013-05-09/parks-and-recreation-renewed-for-season-6/ Parks and Recreation Renewed for Season 6.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140112041630/http://www.ismyshowcancelled.com/article/2013-05-09/parks-and-recreation-renewed-for-season-6/ |date=January 12, 2014 }} ismyshowcancelled.com on May 9, 2013.</ref> NBC had a financial incentive to continue the series, as it owns the distribution rights via its [[NBCUniversal Television Distribution]] company: the sixth season put the series over the [[100 episodes]] milestone, making it more viable for [[Broadcast syndication|syndication]].\n{{#section-h:List of Parks and Recreation episodes|Ratings}}\n\n===Accolades===\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Parks and Recreation}}\n[[File:Mike Schur and-the cast of Parks and Recreation at the 71st Annual Peabody Awards.jpg|thumb|right|Mike Schur accepts the Peabody for ''Parks and Recreation''. He is joined on stage by Retta, Jim O'Heir, Aubrey Plaza, Aziz Ansari, Adam Scott, Nick Offerman and Amy Poehler at the 71st Annual Peabody Awards.]]\n\nIn 2010, Amy Poehler was nominated for a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Lead Actress in a Comedy Series]] for her work in the second season. Also that year, ''Parks and Recreation'' was nominated for the [[TCA Awards|Television Critics Association Award]] for Outstanding Achievement in Comedy and Individual Achievement in Comedy for Nick Offerman for his work in the second season.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Television Critics Association Announces 2010 TCA Awards Winners |publisher=[[Television Critics Association]] |year=2010 |url=http://tvcritics.org/tca-awards/ |accessdate=January 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vzhs9lsk?url=http://tvcritics.org/tca-awards/ |archivedate=January 25, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=MacKenzie |first=Carina Adly |title=Television Critics Award nominations: 'Glee' and 'Modern Family' showdown |publisher=[[Zap2it]] |date=July 30, 2010 |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2010/07/television-critics-award-nominations-glee-and-modern-family-showdown.html |accessdate=January 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vzjREOl3?url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2010/07/television-critics-award-nominations-glee-and-modern-family-showdown.html |archivedate=January 25, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref> The second-season premiere episode, \"Pawnee Zoo\", won the [[GLAAD Media Award]] for Outstanding Individual Episode (in a Series without a Regular LGBT Character).<ref>{{cite web|title=Award Recipients for the 21st Annual GLAAD Media Awards |publisher=[[GLAAD Media Award]]s |date=March 2010 |url=http://www.glaad.org/mediaawards/21/ny/recipients |accessdate=March 14, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vv4uwQAm?url=http://www.glaad.org/mediaawards/21/ny/recipients |archivedate=January 22, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Ram |first=Archana |title='Brothers and Sisters' and 'Parks and Recreation' among winners at GLAAD Media Awards |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=March 14, 2010 |url=http://news-briefs.ew.com/2010/03/14/glaad-awards-brothers-sisters-parks-recreation/ |accessdate=March 15, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vv4wVEmI?url=http://news-briefs.ew.com/2010/03/14/glaad-awards-brothers-sisters-parks-recreation/ |archivedate=January 22, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref> Also in 2010, ''Parks and Recreation'' received two nominations from ''Entertainment Weekly''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[EWwy Awards]]: Best Comedy Series and Best Supporting Actor in a Comedy Series for Offerman.<ref>{{cite news|last=Slezak |first=Michael |title=2010 Emmy Awards: Best Comedy Series: Nominee No. 4 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=August 20, 2010 |url=https://ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20300978_20412761,00.html#20823310 |accessdate=June 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zYCljF8E?url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20300978_20412761,00.html |archivedate=June 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Slezak |first=Michael |title=2010 Emmy Awards: Best Supporting Actor in a Comedy: Nominee No. 3 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=August 20, 2010 |url=https://ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20300978_20412761,00.html#20822782 |accessdate=June 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zYCVtaD9?url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20300978_20412761,00.html |archivedate=June 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, ''Parks and Recreation'' was nominated for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series]] and Amy Poehler received her second Emmy nomination for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Comedy Series.<ref>{{cite news|title=2011 Primetime Emmy Award nominees |work=[[USA Today]] |date=July 14, 2011 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/televisionawards/emmys/2011-07-15-emmy-nominations-list_n.htm |accessdate=July 14, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/60AmsINUz?url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/television/televisionawards/emmys/2011-07-15-emmy-nominations-list_n.htm |archivedate=July 14, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=de Moraes |first=Lisa |author-link=Lisa de Moraes |title=Emmy nominations: Controversial 'Kennedy' miniseries snags multiple nods |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=July 14, 2011 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/tv-column/post/emmy-nominations-controversial-kennedy-miniseries-snags-multiple-nods/2011/07/13/gIQAfD19DI_blog.html |accessdate=July 14, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/60Aog7ja3?url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/tv-column/post/emmy-nominations-controversial-kennedy-miniseries-snags-multiple-nods/2011/07/13/gIQAfD19DI_blog.html |archivedate=July 14, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref> In June 2011, ''Parks and Recreation'' was nominated for three awards for the inaugural Critics' Choice Television Awards: Best Comedy Series, Best Lead Actress in a Comedy Series for Poehler, and Best Supporting Actor in a Comedy Series for Nick Offerman.<ref>{{cite news|title='Family' up for 6 Critics' Choice Awards |publisher=[[United Press International]] |date=June 6, 2011 |url=http://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/TV/2011/06/06/Family-up-for-6-Critics-Choice-Awards/UPI-50241307391555/ |accessdate=June 8, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zYD350Rd?url=http://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/TV/2011/06/06/Family-up-for-6-Critics-Choice-Awards/UPI-50241307391555/ |archivedate=June 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=O'Neal |first=Sean |title=The Critics' Choice Television Awards liked ''Community'', ''Parks And Recreation'', ''Justified'', other shows TV critics like |publisher=The Onion |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=June 6, 2011 |url=https://avclub.com/articles/the-critics-choice-television-awards-liked-communi,57073/ |accessdate=June 8, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zYD350Rd?url=http://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/TV/2011/06/06/Family-up-for-6-Critics-Choice-Awards/UPI-50241307391555/ |archivedate=June 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref> Also that month, ''Parks and Recreation'' was nominated for four TCA Awards: Program of the Year, Outstanding Achievement in Comedy, and Individual Achievement in Comedy for Offerman and Poehler. Offerman hosted the TCA Awards ceremony that year.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sepinwall |first=Alan |authorlink=Alan Sepinwall |title=Television Critics Association Awards nominees include 'Game of Thrones,' 'Justified,' 'Parks and Recreation' and more |work=[[HitFix]] |date=June 13, 2011 |url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/tca-awards-nominees-include-game-of-thrones-justified-parks-and-recreation-and-more |accessdate=June 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zYDFRH5e?url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/tca-awards-nominees-include-game-of-thrones-justified-parks-and-recreation-and-more |archivedate=June 19, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2014, Amy Poehler won her first Golden Globe award for her portrayal of Leslie Knope. Poehler was hosting the ceremony along with [[Tina Fey]].\n\n==Home media==\n===DVD===\nThe first season of ''Parks and Recreation'' was released on DVD in [[DVD region code|region 1]] on September 8, 2009. The DVD included all six episodes, as well as an \"Extended Producer's Cut\" of the season finale, \"Rock Show\". The disc also included cast and crew commentary tracks for each episode, as well as about 30&nbsp;minutes of deleted scenes.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"Crank: High Voltage\"; \"Fringe\"; \"Homicide\"; \"The No. 1 Ladies Detective Agency\" |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |last=Murray |first=Noel |date=September 8, 2009 |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2009/sep/06/entertainment/ca-new6/2 |accessdate=September 19, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5uFU97ngp?url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/sep/06/entertainment/ca-new6/2 |archivedate=November 15, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref> The second season was released in a four-disc set in region&nbsp;1 on November 30, 2010. They included extended episodes for \"The Master Plan\" and \"Freddy Spaghetti\", as well as two-and-a-half hours of deleted scenes, a third season preview and additional video clips. Audio commentaries were recorded for the episodes \"Sister City\", \"Ron and Tammy\", \"Hunting Trip\", \"Woman of the Year\", \"The Master Plan\" and \"Freddy Spaghetti\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Bailey |first=Jason |title=Parks & Recreation: Season Two |publisher=[[DVD Talk]] |date=November 30, 2010 |url=https://dvdtalk.com/reviews/46236/parks-recreation-season-two/ |accessdate=November 30, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5wBgsqFCa?url=http://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/46236/parks-recreation-season-two/ |archivedate=February 2, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref>\n\n''Parks and Recreation'' is not available on [[Blu-ray]] for any season despite airing in high definition and its availability in HD through streaming; the episode \"The Hunting Trip\" is available as a bonus feature on the Blu-ray set for [[The Office (U.S. season 6)|Season Six]] of ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'', making it the only ''Parks and Recreation'' episode on Blu-ray.<ref>{{cite web |title= The Office: Season Six bonus features |url= http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/The-Office-Season-Six-Blu-ray/11106/#Review |website= Blu-ray.com |accessdate= June 17, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150101190148/http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/The-Office-Season-Six-Blu-ray/11106/#Review |archive-date= January 1, 2015 |url-status=live |df= mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Digital===\nIndividual episodes can also be purchased through various digital distribution platforms.\n\n== Possible revival ==\nIn March 2019, during the tenth anniversary reunion at [[PaleyFest]], the cast confirmed they would return for a revival of the series, if series creator Michael Schur \"came up with an original, new idea\". Schur stated, \"I would never ever say never. The chance to do it again, should it arise, would be incredible, but we would only do it if we all felt like there was something compelling us to do it. If one single person said no, we wouldn't do it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/parks-and-rec-revival-10th-anniversary-1203169893/ |title=\u2018Parks and Recreation\u2019 Cast Talks Possibility of a Revival at 10th Anniversary Reunion |last=Moreau |first=Jordan |date=March 22, 2019 |website=Variety |access-date=May 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Parks and Recreation}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.nbc.com/parks-and-recreation}} on [[NBC]]\n* {{IMDb title|id=1266020}}\n* {{tv.com show|parks-and-recreation|Parks and Recreation}}\n\n{{Parks and Recreation Episodes}}\n{{TCA Award for Outstanding Achievement in Comedy}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parks And Recreation}}\n[[Category:Parks and Recreation| ]]\n[[Category:2000s American mockumentary television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American political comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American satirical television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American single-camera sitcoms]]\n[[Category:2000s American workplace comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2009 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s American mockumentary television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American political comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American satirical television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American single-camera sitcoms]]\n[[Category:2010s American workplace comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2015 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:Peabody Award-winning television programs]]\n[[Category:Political satirical television series]]\n[[Category:Television series by 3 Arts Entertainment]]\n[[Category:Television series by Fremulon]]\n[[Category:Television series by Universal Television]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Indiana]]\n", "name_user": "Brojam", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRatings", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parks_and_Recreation"}
{"title_page": "Carcharodontosauridae", "text_new": "{{Automatic taxobox\n| taxon = Carcharodontosauridae\n| name = Carcharodontosaurids\n| fossil_range = [[Late Jurassic]]&ndash;[[Late Cretaceous]],<ref name=Azevedoetal2013/> {{Fossil range|154|91|}}\n| image = Acrocanthosaurus_Hendrickx.jpg\n| image_caption = Skull of ''[[Acrocanthosaurus atokensis]]'', [[North Carolina Museum of Natural Sciences]] \n| authority = [[Ernst Stromer|Stromer]], 1931\n| type_species = {{extinct}}''[[Carcharodontosaurus saharicus]]''\n| type_species_authority = Deperet & Savornin, 1925\n| subdivision_ranks = Subgroups\n| subdivision =\n* {{extinct}}''[[Acrocanthosaurus]]''\n\n* {{extinct}}''[[Concavenator]]''\n* {{extinct}}''[[Eocarcharia]]''\n* {{extinct}}''[[Kelmayisaurus]]''<ref name=\"Kelmayisaurus\"/>\n* {{extinct}}''[[Lajasvenator]]''\n* {{extinct}}''[[Sauroniops]]''\n* {{extinct}}''[[Shaochilong]]''\n* {{extinct}}''[[Taurovenator]]''\n* {{extinct}}''[[Veterupristisaurus]]''\n* {{extinct}}[[Carcharodontosaurinae]]<ref name=\"sciencedirect.com\">{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/j.cretres.2013.04.001 | title=Evolution of the carnivorous dinosaurs during the Cretaceous: The evidence from Patagonia | journal=Cretaceous Research | date=2013 | volume=45 | pages=174\u2013215 | first=Fernando E. | last=Novas}}</ref>\n** {{extinct}}''[[Carcharodontosaurus]]''\n** {{extinct}}'''Giganotosaurini'''\n*** {{extinct}}''[[Giganotosaurus]]''\n*** {{extinct}}''[[Mapusaurus]]''\n*** {{extinct}}''[[Tyrannotitan]]''\n| synonyms =\n* '''Acrocanthosauridae''' <small>Molnar, 2003</small>\n}}\n\n'''Carcharodontosaurids''' (from the [[Greek language|Greek]] \u03ba\u03b1\u03c1\u03c7\u03b1\u03c1\u03bf\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03cc\u03c3\u03b1\u03c5\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2, ''carcharodont\u00f3sauros'': \"shark-toothed lizards\") were a group of carnivorous [[theropod]] [[dinosaur]]s. In 1931 [[Ernst Stromer]] named Carcharodontosauridae as a [[Family (biology)|family]], which, in modern [[paleontology]],  indicates a [[clade]] within [[Carnosauria]]. Carcharodontosaurids included some of the largest land predators ever known: ''[[Giganotosaurus]]'', ''[[Mapusaurus]]'', ''[[Carcharodontosaurus]]'', and ''[[Tyrannotitan]]'' all rivaled or possibly slightly exceeded ''[[Tyrannosaurus]]'' in length. A 2015 paper by Christophe Hendrickx and colleagues gives a maximum length estimate of 14 meters (46 feet) for the largest carcharodontosaurids, while the smallest carcharodontosaurids were estimated to have been at least 6 meters (20 feet) long.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Hendrickx, Christophe; Hartman, Scott A.; Mateus, Oct\u00e1vio (2015): An Overview of Non- Avian Theropod Discoveries and Classification. PalArch's Journal of Vertebrate Palaeontology, 12 (1) pp. 1-73}}</ref>\n\n==Evolution==\n[[File:Concavenator_Skull_diagram.svg|thumb|left|Restoration of the crushed skull of ''[[Concavenator]]'']]\nAlong with the [[Spinosauridae|spinosaurids]], carcharodontosaurids were the largest predators in the early and middle [[Cretaceous]] throughout [[Gondwana]], with species also present in North America (''[[Acrocanthosaurus]]''), Europe (''[[Concavenator]]'') and Asia (''[[Shaochilong]]'').<ref name=brusatteetal2009>{{cite journal | last1 = Brusatte | first1 = S. | last2 = Benson | first2 = R. | last3 = Chure | first3 = D. | last4 = Xu | first4 = X. | last5 = Sullivan | first5 = C. | last6 = Hone | first6 = D. | year = 2009 | title = The first definitive carcharodontosaurid (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from Asia and the delayed ascent of tyrannosaurids | url = | journal = Naturwissenschaften | volume =  96| issue = | pages =  1051\u20138| doi = 10.1007/s00114-009-0565-2 | pmid = 19488730 }}</ref> Carcharodontosaurids range throughout the Cretaceous from the [[Barremian]] (127-121 million years ago) to the [[Turonian]] (93-89 million years ago). Past the Turonian, they might have been replaced by the smaller [[Abelisauridae|abelisaurids]] in Gondwana and by [[Tyrannosauridae|tyrannosaurids]] in North America and Asia. According to [[Fernando Novas]] and colleagues, the disappearance of not only carcharodontosaurids but also [[Spinosauridae|spinosaurids]] and other fauna in both Gondwana and North America seem to indicate that this faunal replacement occurred on a global scale.<ref name=\"novasetal2005\">Novas, de Valais, Vickers-Rich, and Rich. (2005). \"A large Cretaceous theropod from Patagonia, Argentina, and the evolution of carcharodontosaurids.\" ''Naturwissenschaften'',</ref> While some teeth and a [[maxilla]] discovered in [[Maastrichtian]] deposits of [[Brazil]] have been assigned to carcharodontosaurids, possibly extending their range,<ref name=Azevedoetal2013>{{cite journal |author=Rodrigo P. Fernandes de Azevedo |author2=Felipe Medeiros Simbras |author3=Miguel Rodrigues Furtado |author4=Carlos Roberto A. Candeiro |author5=L\u00edlian Paglarelli Bergqvist |last-author-amp=yes |year=2013 |title=First Brazilian carcharodontosaurid and other new theropod dinosaur fossils from the Campanian\u2013Maastrichtian Presidente Prudente Formation, S\u00e3o Paulo State, southeastern Brazil |journal=Cretaceous Research |volume=40 |pages=131\u2013142 |doi=10.1016/j.cretres.2012.06.004}}</ref><ref name=Candeiroetal2012>{{cite journal|author1=Carlos Roberto Candeiro |author2=Philip Currie |author3=L\u00edlian Bergqvist |year=2012 |title=Theropod teeth from the Mar\u00edlia Formation (late Maastrichtian) at the Paleontological Site of Peir\u00f3polis in Minas Gerais State, Brazil |journal=[[Brazilian Journal of Geology|Revista Brasileira de Geoci\u00eancias]] |volume=42 |issue=2 |pages=323\u2013330 |url=http://rbg.sbgeo.org.br/index.php/rbg/article/view/1622 |doi=10.5327/z0375-75362012000200008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222053906/http://rbg.sbgeo.org.br/index.php/rbg/article/view/1622 |archivedate=2014-02-22 }}</ref> this identification has been subsequently rejected and the material assigned to abelisaurids after better examination.<ref name=\"2017brazicarch\">{{cite journal | last1 = Delcourt | first1 = R. | last2 = Grillo | first2 = O.N. | title = Carcharodontosaurids remained extinct in the Campanian-Maastrichtian: Reassessment of a fragmentary maxilla from Presidente Prudente Formation, Brazil | journal = Cretaceous Research | volume = 84 | pages = 515\u2013524 | date = 2017 | doi = 10.1016/j.cretres.2017.09.008 }}</ref> In December 2011, Oliver W. M. Rauhut described a new genus and species of carcharodontosaurid from the [[Late Jurassic]] (late [[Kimmeridgian]] to earliest [[Tithonian]] [[faunal stage]], about 154-150&nbsp;[[million years ago]]) of [[Tendaguru Formation]], southeastern [[Tanzania]]. This genus, ''[[Veterupristisaurus]]'' represents the oldest known carcharodontosaurid.<ref name=Veterupristisaurus>{{cite journal |last=Rauhut |first=Oliver W. M. |year=2011 |title=Theropod dinosaurs from the Late Jurassic of Tendaguru (Tanzania) |journal=Special Papers in Palaeontology |volume=86 |issue= |pages=195\u2013239 |doi=10.1111/j.1475-4983.2011.01084.x |doi-broken-date=2020-03-17 |url=https://www.palass.org/publications/special-papers-palaeontology/archive/86/article_pp195-239}}</ref>\n\n==Classification==\n\nThe family Carcharodontosauridae was originally named by [[Ernst Stromer]] in 1931 to include the single newly discovered species ''Carcharodontosaurus saharicus''. A close relative of ''C. saharicus'', ''Giganotosaurus'', was added to the family when it was described in 1995. Additionally, many paleontologists have included ''Acrocanthosaurus'' in this family (Sereno et al. 1996, Harris 1998, Holtz 2000, Rauhut 2003, Eddy & Clarke, 2011, Rauhut 2011), though others place it in the related family [[Allosauridae]] (Currie & Carpenter, 2000; Coria & Currie, 2002). Carcharodontosaurids are characterized by the following morphological characters : Dorsoventral depth of anterior maxillary interdental plates more than twice anteroposterior width, squared, sub-rectangular anterior portion of the dentary, teeth with wrinkled enamel surfaces, presence of four premaxillary alveoli and a premaxillary body taller than long in lateral aspect, opisthocoelous cervical vertebrae with neural spines more than 1.9 times the height of the centrum, large, textured rugosities on the lacrimal and postorbital formed by roofing and forming broad orbital shelves, and a proximomedially inclined femoral head.<ref name=\"conca\">{{cite journal | last1 = Ortega | first1 =  F. | last2 = Escaso | first2 = F. | last3 = Sanz | first3 = J. L. | date = 2010 | title = A bizarre, humped Carcharodontosauria (Theropoda) from the Lower Cretaceous of Spain | journal = Nature | volume = 467 | issue =  7312 | pages = 203\u2013206 | doi = 10.1038/nature09181 | url = http://pagina.jccm.es/museociencias/Ortega_etal_2010_Tero_Concavenator_Ki_Cuenca_esp_nature09181.pdf | pmid=20829793| bibcode = 2010Natur.467..203O }}</ref><ref name=\"acrocr\">{{cite journal | last1 = Eddy | first1 = DR | last2 = Clarke | first2 = JA | date = 2011 | title = New Information on the Cranial Anatomy of ''Acrocanthosaurus atokensis'' and Its Implications for the Phylogeny of Allosauroidea (Dinosauria: Theropoda) | journal = PLOS One | volume = 6 | issue = 3 | pages = e17932 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0017932 | pmid=21445312 | pmc=3061882| bibcode = 2011PLoSO...617932E }}</ref>\nWith the discovery of ''Mapusaurus'' in 2006, [[Rodolfo Coria]] and [[Phil Currie]] erected a subfamily of Carcharodontosauridae, the Giganotosaurinae, to contain the most advanced South American species, which they found to be more closely related to each other than to the African and European forms. Coria and Currie did not formally refer ''Tyrannotitan'' to this subfamily, pending a more detailed description of that genus, but noted that based on characteristics of the femur, it may be a gigantosaurin as well.<ref name=\"coria&currie2006\">{{cite journal | last1 = Coria | first1 = R.A. | last2 = Currie | first2 = P.J. | year = 2006 | title = A new carcharodontosaurid (Dinosauria, Theropoda) from the Upper Cretaceous of Argentina | url = | journal = Geodiversitas | volume = 28 | issue = 1| pages = 71\u2013118 }}</ref>\n[[File:Carcharodontosaurid scale.svg|thumb|Size comparison of seven carcharodontosaurids]]\nIn 1998 [[Paul Sereno]] defined Carcharodontosauridae as a [[clade]], consisting of ''Carcharodontosaurus'' and all species closer to it than to either ''[[Allosaurus]]'', ''[[Sinraptor]]'', ''[[Monolophosaurus]]'', or ''[[Cryolophosaurus]]''. Therefore, this clade is by definition outside of the clade [[Allosauridae]]. \nThe [[cladogram]] below follows the analysis of Brusatte ''et al.'', 2009.<ref name=brusatteetal2009/>\n\n{{clade| style=font-size:100%;line-height:80%\n|label1='''Carcharodontosauridae'''\n|1={{clade\n   |1=''[[Neovenator]]''[[File:Neovenator.png|80px]]\n   |2={{clade\n      |1={{clade\n         |1=''[[Acrocanthosaurus]]''[[File:Acrocanthosaurus restoration.jpg|85px]]\n         |2=''[[Eocarcharia]]'' [[File:Eocarcharia, improved.png|55px]] }}\n      |2={{clade\n         |1=''[[Shaochilong]]'' [[File:Shaochilong.jpg|80px]]\n         |2=''[[Tyrannotitan]]''\n         |3={{clade\n            |1=''[[Carcharodontosaurus]]'' [[File:Carcharodontosaurus.png|80px]]\n            |label2=Giganotosaurinae\n            |2={{clade \n               |1=''[[Giganotosaurus]]'' [[File:Giganotos Db.jpg|80px]]\n               |2=''[[Mapusaurus]]'' [[File:Mapusaurus Roseae restoration.png|80px]] }} }} }} }} }} }}\n\nCladogram after Ortega ''et al.'', 2010<ref name=\"conca\"/>\n\n{{clade| style=font-size:100%;line-height:80%\n|label1='''Carcharodontosauridae'''\n|1={{clade\n   |1=''[[Eocarcharia]]'' [[File:Eocarcharia, improved.png|55px]]\n   |2={{clade\n      |1=''[[Concavenator]]''[[File:Concavenator corcovatus by Daniel Vidal 2012.png|80px]]\n      |2={{clade\n         |1=''[[Acrocanthosaurus]]'' [[File:Acrocanthosaurus restoration.jpg|85px]]\n         |2={{clade\n            |1=''[[Shaochilong]]'' [[File:Shaochilong.jpg|80px]]\n            |2={{clade\n               |1=''[[Tyrannotitan]]''\n               |2={{clade\n                  |1=''[[Carcharodontosaurus]]'' [[File:Carcharodontosaurus.png|80px]]\n                  |2=''[[Giganotosaurus]]'' [[File:Giganotos Db.jpg|80px]]\n                  |3=''[[Mapusaurus]]'' [[File:Mapusaurus Roseae restoration.png|80px]] }} }} }} }} }} }} }}\n\nCladogram after Novas ''et al.'', 2013<ref name=\"sciencedirect.com\"/>\n\n{{clade| style=font-size:100%;line-height:80%\n|1={{clade\n   |1=''[[Allosaurus]]'' [[File:Allosaurus Revised.jpg|80px]]\n   |label2='''Carcharodontosauridae'''\n   |2={{clade\n      |1=''[[Neovenator]]''[[File:Neovenator.png|80px]]\n      |2=''[[Eocarcharia]]'' [[File:Eocarcharia, improved.png|55px]]\n      |3=''[[Concavenator]]''[[File:Concavenator corcovatus by Daniel Vidal 2012.png|80px]]\n      |4={{clade\n         |1=''[[Acrocanthosaurus]]''[[File:Acrocanthosaurus restoration.jpg|85px]]\n         |2={{clade\n            |1=''[[Shaochilong]]'' [[File:Shaochilong.jpg|80px]]\n            |label2=Carcharodontosaurinae\n            |2={{clade\n               |1=''[[Carcharodontosaurus]]'' [[File:Carcharodontosaurus.png|80px]]\n               |label2=Giganotosaurini\n               |2={{clade\n                  |1=''[[Tyrannotitan]]''\n                  |2={{clade\n                     |1=''[[Mapusaurus]]'' [[File:Mapusaurus Roseae restoration.png|80px]]\n                     |2=''[[Giganotosaurus]]'' [[File:Giganotos Db.jpg|80px]]}} }} }} }} }} }} }} }}\n\n[[File:Acrocanthosaurusskeleton.jpg|thumb|Mounted ''Acrocanthosaurus'' skeleton (NCSM 14345) at the [[North Carolina Museum of Natural Sciences]].]]\nThe placement of ''Acrocanthosaurus'' is unclear, with most<ref name=\"acrocr\"/> researchers favoring Carcharodontosauridae and others favoring Allosauridae. In 2011, a redescription of ''Kelmayisaurus'' by Stephen L. Brusatte, Roger B. J. Benson and Xing Xu found it to be valid genus of Carcharodontosauridae. A [[phylogenetic]] analysis of [[Tetanurae]] recovered ''K. petrolicus'' as a basal carcharodontosaurid in a [[polytomy|trichotomy]] with ''[[Eocarcharia]]'' and a clade comprising more [[Synapomorphy|derived]] carcharodontosaurids.<ref name=\"Kelmayisaurus\">{{cite journal |year=2012 |title=A reassessment of ''Kelmayisaurus petrolicus'', a large theropod dinosaur from the Early Cretaceous of China |url=http://www.app.pan.pl/archive/published/app56/app20100125_acc.pdf |journal=Acta Palaeontologica Polonica |volume=57 |pages= 65\u201372|doi=10.4202/app.2010.0125 |author1=Stephen L. Brusatte |author2=Roger B. J. Benson |author3=Xing Xu |issue=1}}</ref> ''[[Bahariasaurus]]'' has also been proposed as a carcharodontosaurid, but its remains are too scarce to be certain.\n\nCarcharodontosaurids have been proposed as more closely related to abelisaurids, as opposed to the allosaurids. This is due to these two clades sharing some [[cranium|cranial]] features (see link below). However, these similarities appear to derive from parallel evolution between these two groups. A larger number of cranial and [[postcranial]] characters support their relationship with allosaurids.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikispecies}}\n{{Portal|Dinosaurs}}\n*[http://dml.cmnh.org/1999Mar/msg00493.html Carcharodontosauridae/Abelisauridae]\n*[http://dml.cmnh.org/1999Mar/msg00504.html Carcharodontosauridae/Abelisauridae 2]\n\n{{Theropoda|A.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q131334}}\n\n[[Category:Carcharodontosaurids| ]]\n[[Category:Carcharodontosauria]]\n[[Category:Kimmeridgian first appearances]]\n[[Category:Kimmeridgian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Tithonian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Berriasian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Valanginian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Hauterivian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Barremian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Aptian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Albian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Cenomanian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Turonian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Turonian extinctions]]\n", "text_old": "{{Automatic taxobox\n| taxon = Carcharodontosauridae\n| name = Carcharodontosaurids\n| fossil_range = [[Late Jurassic]]&ndash;[[Late Cretaceous]],<ref name=Azevedoetal2013/> {{Fossil range|154|91|}}\n| image = Acrocanthosaurus_Hendrickx.jpg\n| image_caption = Skull of ''[[Acrocanthosaurus atokensis]]'', [[North Carolina Museum of Natural Sciences]] \n| authority = [[Ernst Stromer|Stromer]], 1931\n| type_species = {{extinct}}''[[Carcharodontosaurus saharicus]]''\n| type_species_authority = Deperet & Savornin, 1925\n| subdivision_ranks = Subgroups\n| subdivision =\n* {{extinct}}''[[Acrocanthosaurus]]''\n* {{extinct}}''[[Altispinax]]''?\n* {{extinct}}''[[Concavenator]]''\n* {{extinct}}''[[Eocarcharia]]''\n* {{extinct}}''[[Kelmayisaurus]]''<ref name=\"Kelmayisaurus\"/>\n* {{extinct}}''[[Lajasvenator]]''\n* {{extinct}}''[[Sauroniops]]''\n* {{extinct}}''[[Shaochilong]]''\n* {{extinct}}''[[Siamraptor]]''?\n* {{extinct}}''[[Taurovenator]]''\n* {{extinct}}''[[Veterupristisaurus]]''\n* {{extinct}}[[Carcharodontosaurinae]]<ref name=\"sciencedirect.com\">{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/j.cretres.2013.04.001 | title=Evolution of the carnivorous dinosaurs during the Cretaceous: The evidence from Patagonia | journal=Cretaceous Research | date=2013 | volume=45 | pages=174\u2013215 | first=Fernando E. | last=Novas}}</ref>\n** {{extinct}}''[[Carcharodontosaurus]]''\n** {{extinct}}'''Giganotosaurini'''\n*** {{extinct}}''[[Giganotosaurus]]''\n*** {{extinct}}''[[Mapusaurus]]''\n*** {{extinct}}''[[Tyrannotitan]]''\n| synonyms =\n* '''Acrocanthosauridae''' <small>Molnar, 2003</small>\n}}\n\n'''Carcharodontosaurids''' (from the [[Greek language|Greek]] \u03ba\u03b1\u03c1\u03c7\u03b1\u03c1\u03bf\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03cc\u03c3\u03b1\u03c5\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2, ''carcharodont\u00f3sauros'': \"shark-toothed lizards\") were a group of carnivorous [[theropod]] [[dinosaur]]s. In 1931 [[Ernst Stromer]] named Carcharodontosauridae as a [[Family (biology)|family]], which, in modern [[paleontology]],  indicates a [[clade]] within [[Carnosauria]]. Carcharodontosaurids included some of the largest land predators ever known: ''[[Giganotosaurus]]'', ''[[Mapusaurus]]'', ''[[Carcharodontosaurus]]'', and ''[[Tyrannotitan]]'' all rivaled or possibly slightly exceeded ''[[Tyrannosaurus]]'' in length. A 2015 paper by Christophe Hendrickx and colleagues gives a maximum length estimate of 14 meters (46 feet) for the largest carcharodontosaurids, while the smallest carcharodontosaurids were estimated to have been at least 6 meters (20 feet) long.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Hendrickx, Christophe; Hartman, Scott A.; Mateus, Oct\u00e1vio (2015): An Overview of Non- Avian Theropod Discoveries and Classification. PalArch's Journal of Vertebrate Palaeontology, 12 (1) pp. 1-73}}</ref>\n\n==Evolution==\n[[File:Concavenator_Skull_diagram.svg|thumb|left|Restoration of the crushed skull of ''[[Concavenator]]'']]\nAlong with the [[Spinosauridae|spinosaurids]], carcharodontosaurids were the largest predators in the early and middle [[Cretaceous]] throughout [[Gondwana]], with species also present in North America (''[[Acrocanthosaurus]]''), Europe (''[[Concavenator]]'') and Asia (''[[Shaochilong]]'').<ref name=brusatteetal2009>{{cite journal | last1 = Brusatte | first1 = S. | last2 = Benson | first2 = R. | last3 = Chure | first3 = D. | last4 = Xu | first4 = X. | last5 = Sullivan | first5 = C. | last6 = Hone | first6 = D. | year = 2009 | title = The first definitive carcharodontosaurid (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from Asia and the delayed ascent of tyrannosaurids | url = | journal = Naturwissenschaften | volume =  96| issue = | pages =  1051\u20138| doi = 10.1007/s00114-009-0565-2 | pmid = 19488730 }}</ref> Carcharodontosaurids range throughout the Cretaceous from the [[Barremian]] (127-121 million years ago) to the [[Turonian]] (93-89 million years ago). Past the Turonian, they might have been replaced by the smaller [[Abelisauridae|abelisaurids]] in Gondwana and by [[Tyrannosauridae|tyrannosaurids]] in North America and Asia. According to [[Fernando Novas]] and colleagues, the disappearance of not only carcharodontosaurids but also [[Spinosauridae|spinosaurids]] and other fauna in both Gondwana and North America seem to indicate that this faunal replacement occurred on a global scale.<ref name=\"novasetal2005\">Novas, de Valais, Vickers-Rich, and Rich. (2005). \"A large Cretaceous theropod from Patagonia, Argentina, and the evolution of carcharodontosaurids.\" ''Naturwissenschaften'',</ref> While some teeth and a [[maxilla]] discovered in [[Maastrichtian]] deposits of [[Brazil]] have been assigned to carcharodontosaurids, possibly extending their range,<ref name=Azevedoetal2013>{{cite journal |author=Rodrigo P. Fernandes de Azevedo |author2=Felipe Medeiros Simbras |author3=Miguel Rodrigues Furtado |author4=Carlos Roberto A. Candeiro |author5=L\u00edlian Paglarelli Bergqvist |last-author-amp=yes |year=2013 |title=First Brazilian carcharodontosaurid and other new theropod dinosaur fossils from the Campanian\u2013Maastrichtian Presidente Prudente Formation, S\u00e3o Paulo State, southeastern Brazil |journal=Cretaceous Research |volume=40 |pages=131\u2013142 |doi=10.1016/j.cretres.2012.06.004}}</ref><ref name=Candeiroetal2012>{{cite journal|author1=Carlos Roberto Candeiro |author2=Philip Currie |author3=L\u00edlian Bergqvist |year=2012 |title=Theropod teeth from the Mar\u00edlia Formation (late Maastrichtian) at the Paleontological Site of Peir\u00f3polis in Minas Gerais State, Brazil |journal=[[Brazilian Journal of Geology|Revista Brasileira de Geoci\u00eancias]] |volume=42 |issue=2 |pages=323\u2013330 |url=http://rbg.sbgeo.org.br/index.php/rbg/article/view/1622 |doi=10.5327/z0375-75362012000200008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222053906/http://rbg.sbgeo.org.br/index.php/rbg/article/view/1622 |archivedate=2014-02-22 }}</ref> this identification has been subsequently rejected and the material assigned to abelisaurids after better examination.<ref name=\"2017brazicarch\">{{cite journal | last1 = Delcourt | first1 = R. | last2 = Grillo | first2 = O.N. | title = Carcharodontosaurids remained extinct in the Campanian-Maastrichtian: Reassessment of a fragmentary maxilla from Presidente Prudente Formation, Brazil | journal = Cretaceous Research | volume = 84 | pages = 515\u2013524 | date = 2017 | doi = 10.1016/j.cretres.2017.09.008 }}</ref> In December 2011, Oliver W. M. Rauhut described a new genus and species of carcharodontosaurid from the [[Late Jurassic]] (late [[Kimmeridgian]] to earliest [[Tithonian]] [[faunal stage]], about 154-150&nbsp;[[million years ago]]) of [[Tendaguru Formation]], southeastern [[Tanzania]]. This genus, ''[[Veterupristisaurus]]'' represents the oldest known carcharodontosaurid.<ref name=Veterupristisaurus>{{cite journal |last=Rauhut |first=Oliver W. M. |year=2011 |title=Theropod dinosaurs from the Late Jurassic of Tendaguru (Tanzania) |journal=Special Papers in Palaeontology |volume=86 |issue= |pages=195\u2013239 |doi=10.1111/j.1475-4983.2011.01084.x |doi-broken-date=2020-03-17 |url=https://www.palass.org/publications/special-papers-palaeontology/archive/86/article_pp195-239}}</ref>\n\n==Classification==\n\nThe family Carcharodontosauridae was originally named by [[Ernst Stromer]] in 1931 to include the single newly discovered species ''Carcharodontosaurus saharicus''. A close relative of ''C. saharicus'', ''Giganotosaurus'', was added to the family when it was described in 1995. Additionally, many paleontologists have included ''Acrocanthosaurus'' in this family (Sereno et al. 1996, Harris 1998, Holtz 2000, Rauhut 2003, Eddy & Clarke, 2011, Rauhut 2011), though others place it in the related family [[Allosauridae]] (Currie & Carpenter, 2000; Coria & Currie, 2002). Carcharodontosaurids are characterized by the following morphological characters : Dorsoventral depth of anterior maxillary interdental plates more than twice anteroposterior width, squared, sub-rectangular anterior portion of the dentary, teeth with wrinkled enamel surfaces, presence of four premaxillary alveoli and a premaxillary body taller than long in lateral aspect, opisthocoelous cervical vertebrae with neural spines more than 1.9 times the height of the centrum, large, textured rugosities on the lacrimal and postorbital formed by roofing and forming broad orbital shelves, and a proximomedially inclined femoral head.<ref name=\"conca\">{{cite journal | last1 = Ortega | first1 =  F. | last2 = Escaso | first2 = F. | last3 = Sanz | first3 = J. L. | date = 2010 | title = A bizarre, humped Carcharodontosauria (Theropoda) from the Lower Cretaceous of Spain | journal = Nature | volume = 467 | issue =  7312 | pages = 203\u2013206 | doi = 10.1038/nature09181 | url = http://pagina.jccm.es/museociencias/Ortega_etal_2010_Tero_Concavenator_Ki_Cuenca_esp_nature09181.pdf | pmid=20829793| bibcode = 2010Natur.467..203O }}</ref><ref name=\"acrocr\">{{cite journal | last1 = Eddy | first1 = DR | last2 = Clarke | first2 = JA | date = 2011 | title = New Information on the Cranial Anatomy of ''Acrocanthosaurus atokensis'' and Its Implications for the Phylogeny of Allosauroidea (Dinosauria: Theropoda) | journal = PLOS One | volume = 6 | issue = 3 | pages = e17932 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0017932 | pmid=21445312 | pmc=3061882| bibcode = 2011PLoSO...617932E }}</ref>\nWith the discovery of ''Mapusaurus'' in 2006, [[Rodolfo Coria]] and [[Phil Currie]] erected a subfamily of Carcharodontosauridae, the Giganotosaurinae, to contain the most advanced South American species, which they found to be more closely related to each other than to the African and European forms. Coria and Currie did not formally refer ''Tyrannotitan'' to this subfamily, pending a more detailed description of that genus, but noted that based on characteristics of the femur, it may be a gigantosaurin as well.<ref name=\"coria&currie2006\">{{cite journal | last1 = Coria | first1 = R.A. | last2 = Currie | first2 = P.J. | year = 2006 | title = A new carcharodontosaurid (Dinosauria, Theropoda) from the Upper Cretaceous of Argentina | url = | journal = Geodiversitas | volume = 28 | issue = 1| pages = 71\u2013118 }}</ref>\n[[File:Carcharodontosaurid scale.svg|thumb|Size comparison of seven carcharodontosaurids]]\nIn 1998 [[Paul Sereno]] defined Carcharodontosauridae as a [[clade]], consisting of ''Carcharodontosaurus'' and all species closer to it than to either ''[[Allosaurus]]'', ''[[Sinraptor]]'', ''[[Monolophosaurus]]'', or ''[[Cryolophosaurus]]''. Therefore, this clade is by definition outside of the clade [[Allosauridae]]. \nThe [[cladogram]] below follows the analysis of Brusatte ''et al.'', 2009.<ref name=brusatteetal2009/>\n\n{{clade| style=font-size:100%;line-height:80%\n|label1='''Carcharodontosauridae'''\n|1={{clade\n   |1=''[[Neovenator]]''[[File:Neovenator.png|80px]]\n   |2={{clade\n      |1={{clade\n         |1=''[[Acrocanthosaurus]]''[[File:Acrocanthosaurus restoration.jpg|85px]]\n         |2=''[[Eocarcharia]]'' [[File:Eocarcharia, improved.png|55px]] }}\n      |2={{clade\n         |1=''[[Shaochilong]]'' [[File:Shaochilong.jpg|80px]]\n         |2=''[[Tyrannotitan]]''\n         |3={{clade\n            |1=''[[Carcharodontosaurus]]'' [[File:Carcharodontosaurus.png|80px]]\n            |label2=Giganotosaurinae\n            |2={{clade \n               |1=''[[Giganotosaurus]]'' [[File:Giganotos Db.jpg|80px]]\n               |2=''[[Mapusaurus]]'' [[File:Mapusaurus Roseae restoration.png|80px]] }} }} }} }} }} }}\n\nCladogram after Ortega ''et al.'', 2010<ref name=\"conca\"/>\n\n{{clade| style=font-size:100%;line-height:80%\n|label1='''Carcharodontosauridae'''\n|1={{clade\n   |1=''[[Eocarcharia]]'' [[File:Eocarcharia, improved.png|55px]]\n   |2={{clade\n      |1=''[[Concavenator]]''[[File:Concavenator corcovatus by Daniel Vidal 2012.png|80px]]\n      |2={{clade\n         |1=''[[Acrocanthosaurus]]'' [[File:Acrocanthosaurus restoration.jpg|85px]]\n         |2={{clade\n            |1=''[[Shaochilong]]'' [[File:Shaochilong.jpg|80px]]\n            |2={{clade\n               |1=''[[Tyrannotitan]]''\n               |2={{clade\n                  |1=''[[Carcharodontosaurus]]'' [[File:Carcharodontosaurus.png|80px]]\n                  |2=''[[Giganotosaurus]]'' [[File:Giganotos Db.jpg|80px]]\n                  |3=''[[Mapusaurus]]'' [[File:Mapusaurus Roseae restoration.png|80px]] }} }} }} }} }} }} }}\n\nCladogram after Novas ''et al.'', 2013<ref name=\"sciencedirect.com\"/>\n\n{{clade| style=font-size:100%;line-height:80%\n|1={{clade\n   |1=''[[Allosaurus]]'' [[File:Allosaurus Revised.jpg|80px]]\n   |label2='''Carcharodontosauridae'''\n   |2={{clade\n      |1=''[[Neovenator]]''[[File:Neovenator.png|80px]]\n      |2=''[[Eocarcharia]]'' [[File:Eocarcharia, improved.png|55px]]\n      |3=''[[Concavenator]]''[[File:Concavenator corcovatus by Daniel Vidal 2012.png|80px]]\n      |4={{clade\n         |1=''[[Acrocanthosaurus]]''[[File:Acrocanthosaurus restoration.jpg|85px]]\n         |2={{clade\n            |1=''[[Shaochilong]]'' [[File:Shaochilong.jpg|80px]]\n            |label2=Carcharodontosaurinae\n            |2={{clade\n               |1=''[[Carcharodontosaurus]]'' [[File:Carcharodontosaurus.png|80px]]\n               |label2=Giganotosaurini\n               |2={{clade\n                  |1=''[[Tyrannotitan]]''\n                  |2={{clade\n                     |1=''[[Mapusaurus]]'' [[File:Mapusaurus Roseae restoration.png|80px]]\n                     |2=''[[Giganotosaurus]]'' [[File:Giganotos Db.jpg|80px]]}} }} }} }} }} }} }} }}\n\n[[File:Acrocanthosaurusskeleton.jpg|thumb|Mounted ''Acrocanthosaurus'' skeleton (NCSM 14345) at the [[North Carolina Museum of Natural Sciences]].]]\nThe placement of ''Acrocanthosaurus'' is unclear, with most<ref name=\"acrocr\"/> researchers favoring Carcharodontosauridae and others favoring Allosauridae. In 2011, a redescription of ''Kelmayisaurus'' by Stephen L. Brusatte, Roger B. J. Benson and Xing Xu found it to be valid genus of Carcharodontosauridae. A [[phylogenetic]] analysis of [[Tetanurae]] recovered ''K. petrolicus'' as a basal carcharodontosaurid in a [[polytomy|trichotomy]] with ''[[Eocarcharia]]'' and a clade comprising more [[Synapomorphy|derived]] carcharodontosaurids.<ref name=\"Kelmayisaurus\">{{cite journal |year=2012 |title=A reassessment of ''Kelmayisaurus petrolicus'', a large theropod dinosaur from the Early Cretaceous of China |url=http://www.app.pan.pl/archive/published/app56/app20100125_acc.pdf |journal=Acta Palaeontologica Polonica |volume=57 |pages= 65\u201372|doi=10.4202/app.2010.0125 |author1=Stephen L. Brusatte |author2=Roger B. J. Benson |author3=Xing Xu |issue=1}}</ref> ''[[Bahariasaurus]]'' has also been proposed as a carcharodontosaurid, but its remains are too scarce to be certain.\n\nCarcharodontosaurids have been proposed as more closely related to abelisaurids, as opposed to the allosaurids. This is due to these two clades sharing some [[cranium|cranial]] features (see link below). However, these similarities appear to derive from parallel evolution between these two groups. A larger number of cranial and [[postcranial]] characters support their relationship with allosaurids.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikispecies}}\n{{Portal|Dinosaurs}}\n*[http://dml.cmnh.org/1999Mar/msg00493.html Carcharodontosauridae/Abelisauridae]\n*[http://dml.cmnh.org/1999Mar/msg00504.html Carcharodontosauridae/Abelisauridae 2]\n\n{{Theropoda|A.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q131334}}\n\n[[Category:Carcharodontosaurids| ]]\n[[Category:Carcharodontosauria]]\n[[Category:Kimmeridgian first appearances]]\n[[Category:Kimmeridgian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Tithonian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Berriasian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Valanginian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Hauterivian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Barremian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Aptian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Albian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Cenomanian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Turonian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Turonian extinctions]]\n", "name_user": "2001:2d8:e128:57ca:8087:b3fe:8529:7a3b", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carcharodontosauridae"}
{"title_page": "Michael Burns (executive)", "text_new": "{{BLPrefimprove|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix          = \n| name                      = \n| honorific_suffix          = \n| image                     = Michael R. Burns.jpg\n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = Burns in 2014\n| native_name               = \n| native_name_lang          = \n| birth_name                = Michael Raymond Burns\n| birth_date                = {{Birth date and age|1958|08|21|}}\n| birth_place               = [[Long Branch, New Jersey]], U.S.\n| death_date                = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place               = \n| death_cause               = \n| alma_mater                = [[Arizona State University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]]) <br> [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]] ([[Master of Business Administration|M.B.A.]])\n| occupation                = Vice Chairman\n| employer                  = [[Lionsgate]]\n| home_town                 = [[New Canaan, Connecticut]]<br> [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n| spouse                    = {{ubl|{{marriage|[[Lori Loughlin]]<br>|1989|1996|end=divorced}}}}{{marriage|[[Pell James]]<br>|2006}}<!-- Do not change without a reliable source -->\n| children                  = \n}}\n\n'''Michael Raymond Burns''' (born August 21, 1958) is an American entertainment executive and Vice Chairman of [[Lionsgate]], a film studio and global content platform. He joined Lionsgate's Board of Directors in 1999 and became Vice Chairman of the studio in March 2000.\n\n\n==Early life==\nBurns was born into an Irish-American Roman Catholic family in [[Long Branch, New Jersey]], on August 21, 1958. His father was an advertising executive and World War II combat veteran who landed on Iwo Jima.<ref>[http://www.tv.com/shows/war-heroes/goin-back-iwo-jima-2363993 \"Goin'Back: Iwo Jima\"], tv.com; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref> His family moved to [[New Canaan, Connecticut]], where he was raised. He later attended [[Arizona State University]], graduating with a B.S. degree in 1980. He earned his M.B.A. from [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]].<ref>[http://www.anderson.ucla.edu/donor-honor-roll-13/board-of-visitors UCLA Anderson Board of Visitors website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714153330/http://www.anderson.ucla.edu/donor-honor-roll-13/board-of-visitors |date=2014-07-14 }}; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nBurns began his career as a sales representative for IBM, where he won recognition as a performance leader. Mr. Burns served as Managing Director and Head of the Office at Prudential Securities Inc.'s Los Angeles Investment Banking Office from 1991 to March 2000.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Agency|first1=RED Interactive|title=Corporate|url=http://www.lionsgate.com/corporate/governance/board-of-directors/|website=www.lionsgate.com|language=en-us}}</ref> He subsequently served for 18 years as a Wall Street executive, joining Shearson/American Express in 1985, where he first became acquainted with [[Jamie Dimon]] (the firm became [[Shearson Lehman|Shearson Lehman Bros.]] in 1990).<ref>[http://www.newsmax.com/Newsfront/jamie-dimon-jpmoprgan-chase/2013/05/15/id/504681 Burns profile], newsmax.com; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref>\n\nHe was named to a series of progressively responsible executive positions during his nine-year tenure at Shearson, becoming a vice president at the age of 26 and a senior vice president at 29. He then joined Prudential Securities as a managing director at the age of 32, serving as head of Prudential's Los Angeles investment banking office, where he specialized in raising equity within the media and entertainment industry.<ref>[http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=708689&privcapId=29605&previousCapId=27536&previousTitle=DEVRY%20 Burns profile], Businessweek.com; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref>\n\nBurns was recruited to join the Board of Directors of Lionsgate, an independent studio known for art house successes such as ''Gods and Monsters'', ''Affliction'' and ''The Red Violin'', in 1999.<ref>[http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/lions-gate-entertainment-corporation-history Lionsgate Funding Universe History]; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref> He and Feltheimer, a former Sony Pictures and New World Entertainment executive, orchestrated a $33 million preferred equity financing in December 1999.<ref>[https://variety.com/2001/tv/news/lions-gate-inks-teuton-pact-1117853753/ Lions Gate inks Teuton Pact], variety.com; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref>\n\nFollowing the recapitalization, Feltheimer and Burns formally joined Lionsgate as Chief Executive Officer and Vice Chairman, respectively.<ref>[http://www.boxofficemojo.com/features/?id=2487 Interview with Michael Burns], boxofficemojo.com; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref>\n\nLionsgate soon generated a string of fiercely independent hits such as ''Monster's Ball'', which earned a Best Actress Academy Award for Halle Berry in 2002, ''Fahrenheit 9/11'', the highest-grossing documentary film of all time, ''Crash'', which surprised the Hollywood community by winning three Oscars,<ref>[http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/78th-winners.html The 78th Academy Awards Nominees and Winners], oscars.org; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref> including Best Picture, in 2006, and ''Saw'', acquired for $1 million from 90 seconds of video and a script, which went on to become the highest-grossing horror franchise of all time, generating $860 million at the worldwide box office.<ref>[http://www.boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=saw.htm SAW Franchise Worldwide Gross], boxofficemojo.com; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref>\n\nAs Lionsgate continued to grow, it listed on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] in August 2004 and diversified into television production and distribution as well as investments in branded channels. The company grew and diversified, acquiring Trimark Holdings (2000), Artisan Entertainment (2003), Redbus Film Distributors, subsequently renamed Lionsgate UK (2005), the Debmar-Mercury television syndication company (2006), TV Guide Network (2009) and Summit Entertainment (2012). In December 2016, Lionsgate acquired the premium pay television platform Starz for $4.4 billion, the largest acquisition in the Company's history.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nLionsgate films and franchises have collectively grossed more than $7 billion at the worldwide box office, and ground-breaking television series such as Orange is the New Black, Nashville, Casual and the iconic Mad Men, which won four consecutive Best Drama Emmys.<ref>[http://www.emmys.com/shows/mad-men Mad Men Emmys], emmys.com; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref>\n\nThe Company also has a fast-growing games division, a location-based entertainment business that includes theme park attractions, rides and exhibitions currently operating or planned in the U.S., UK, Europe, the Middle East and China, and its ground-breaking Atom Tickets partnership with Disney and Fox.\n\nIn a January 2014 story, \"A Star is Born\", chronicling Lionsgate's rise, ''[[The Economist]]'' proclaimed that \"Hollywood has a new star studio with a different approach to the film business\", reporting \"Lionsgate has achieved a level of success no one predicted.\"<ref>[https://www.economist.com/news/business/21595007-hollywood-has-new-star-studio-different-approach-film-business-fighting \"Hollywood Has A New Star Studio\"], economist.com; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Other==\nBurns was a co-founder and Chairman of Novica.com and a co-founder of the Hollywood Stock Exchange. A Republican, he is a contributing writer for ''The Huffington Post'' and ''Newsmax''.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/michael-burns/greenbacks-for-green-card_b_232134.html? \"Greenbacks for Green Cards\"], huffingtonpost.com; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref><ref>[http://www.newsmax.com/Newsfront/republican-party-changes-obama/2012/11/07/id/463294 Michael Burns: Ex Malo Bonum - From Bad Comes Good], newsmax.com; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref>\n\nHe is a member of the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts & Sciences]]. On December 11, 2014, he was elected as an independent director to the Board of Directors of [[Hasbro|Hasbro, Inc.]]<ref>[http://investor.hasbro.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=887244 Hasbro Elects Michael Burns to Board Of Directors], investor.hasbro.com; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref>\n\nHe also serves on the Leadership Council of global first responder International Medical Corps.{{cn|date=January 2020}} In March 2017 he was named Alumni of the Year by [[Arizona State University]].{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\n==Personal==\nBurns was married to actress [[Lori Loughlin]] from 1989 to 1996. He married actress [[Pell James]] in 2006.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/11/fashion/weddings/11JAME.html?_r=0 Pell James, Michael Burns wedding announcement], nytimes.com, June 11, 2006.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/michael-burns/ Huffington Post]\n*[http://www.lionsgate.com/corporate/governance/management/michael-burns/ Lionsgate Corporate Site Biography]\n*{{IMDb name|0122800|Michael Burns}}\n\n{{Lionsgate}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burns, Michael}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:California Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from New Canaan, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Arizona State University alumni]]\n[[Category:UCLA Anderson School of Management alumni]]\n[[Category:American investment bankers]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Catholics from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLPrefimprove|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix          = \n| name                      = \n| honorific_suffix          = \n| image                     = Michael R. Burns.jpg\n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = Burns in 2014\n| native_name               = \n| native_name_lang          = \n| birth_name                = Michael Raymond Burns\n| birth_date                = {{Birth date and age|1958|08|21|}}\n| birth_place               = [[Long Branch, New Jersey]], U.S.\n| death_date                = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place               = \n| death_cause               = \n| alma_mater                = [[Arizona State University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]]) <br> [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]] ([[Master of Business Administration|M.B.A.]])\n| occupation                = Vice Chairman\n| employer                  = [[Lionsgate]]\n| home_town                 = [[New Canaan, Connecticut]]<br> [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n| spouse                    = {{ubl|{{marriage|[[Lori Loughlin]]<br>|1989|1996|end=divorced}}}}{{marriage|[[Pell James]]<br>|2006}}<!-- Do not change without a reliable source -->\n| children                  = \n}}\n\n'''Michael Raymond Burns''' (born August 21, 1958) is an American entertainment executive and Vice Chairman of [[Lionsgate]], a film studio and global content platform. He joined Lionsgate's Board of Directors in 1999 and became Vice Chairman of the studio in March 2000.\n\nn\n\n.<ref>[https://finance.yahoo.com/q?s=LGF Profile], finance.yahoo.com; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBurns was born into an Irish-American Roman Catholic family in [[Long Branch, New Jersey]], on August 21, 1958. His father was an advertising executive and World War II combat veteran who landed on Iwo Jima.<ref>[http://www.tv.com/shows/war-heroes/goin-back-iwo-jima-2363993 \"Goin'Back: Iwo Jima\"], tv.com; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref> His family moved to [[New Canaan, Connecticut]], where he was raised. He later attended [[Arizona State University]], graduating with a B.S. degree in 1980. He earned his M.B.A. from [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]].<ref>[http://www.anderson.ucla.edu/donor-honor-roll-13/board-of-visitors UCLA Anderson Board of Visitors website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714153330/http://www.anderson.ucla.edu/donor-honor-roll-13/board-of-visitors |date=2014-07-14 }}; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nBurns began his career as a sales representative for IBM, where he won recognition as a performance leader. Mr. Burns served as Managing Director and Head of the Office at Prudential Securities Inc.'s Los Angeles Investment Banking Office from 1991 to March 2000.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Agency|first1=RED Interactive|title=Corporate|url=http://www.lionsgate.com/corporate/governance/board-of-directors/|website=www.lionsgate.com|language=en-us}}</ref> He subsequently served for 18 years as a Wall Street executive, joining Shearson/American Express in 1985, where he first became acquainted with [[Jamie Dimon]] (the firm became [[Shearson Lehman|Shearson Lehman Bros.]] in 1990).<ref>[http://www.newsmax.com/Newsfront/jamie-dimon-jpmoprgan-chase/2013/05/15/id/504681 Burns profile], newsmax.com; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref>\n\nHe was named to a series of progressively responsible executive positions during his nine-year tenure at Shearson, becoming a vice president at the age of 26 and a senior vice president at 29. He then joined Prudential Securities as a managing director at the age of 32, serving as head of Prudential's Los Angeles investment banking office, where he specialized in raising equity within the media and entertainment industry.<ref>[http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=708689&privcapId=29605&previousCapId=27536&previousTitle=DEVRY%20 Burns profile], Businessweek.com; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref>\n\nBurns was recruited to join the Board of Directors of Lionsgate, an independent studio known for art house successes such as ''Gods and Monsters'', ''Affliction'' and ''The Red Violin'', in 1999.<ref>[http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/lions-gate-entertainment-corporation-history Lionsgate Funding Universe History]; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref> He and Feltheimer, a former Sony Pictures and New World Entertainment executive, orchestrated a $33 million preferred equity financing in December 1999.<ref>[https://variety.com/2001/tv/news/lions-gate-inks-teuton-pact-1117853753/ Lions Gate inks Teuton Pact], variety.com; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref>\n\nFollowing the recapitalization, Feltheimer and Burns formally joined Lionsgate as Chief Executive Officer and Vice Chairman, respectively.<ref>[http://www.boxofficemojo.com/features/?id=2487 Interview with Michael Burns], boxofficemojo.com; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref>\n\nLionsgate soon generated a string of fiercely independent hits such as ''Monster's Ball'', which earned a Best Actress Academy Award for Halle Berry in 2002, ''Fahrenheit 9/11'', the highest-grossing documentary film of all time, ''Crash'', which surprised the Hollywood community by winning three Oscars,<ref>[http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/78th-winners.html The 78th Academy Awards Nominees and Winners], oscars.org; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref> including Best Picture, in 2006, and ''Saw'', acquired for $1 million from 90 seconds of video and a script, which went on to become the highest-grossing horror franchise of all time, generating $860 million at the worldwide box office.<ref>[http://www.boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=saw.htm SAW Franchise Worldwide Gross], boxofficemojo.com; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref>\n\nAs Lionsgate continued to grow, it listed on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] in August 2004 and diversified into television production and distribution as well as investments in branded channels. The company grew and diversified, acquiring Trimark Holdings (2000), Artisan Entertainment (2003), Redbus Film Distributors, subsequently renamed Lionsgate UK (2005), the Debmar-Mercury television syndication company (2006), TV Guide Network (2009) and Summit Entertainment (2012). In December 2016, Lionsgate acquired the premium pay television platform Starz for $4.4 billion, the largest acquisition in the Company's history.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nLionsgate films and franchises have collectively grossed more than $7 billion at the worldwide box office, and ground-breaking television series such as Orange is the New Black, Nashville, Casual and the iconic Mad Men, which won four consecutive Best Drama Emmys.<ref>[http://www.emmys.com/shows/mad-men Mad Men Emmys], emmys.com; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref>\n\nThe Company also has a fast-growing games division, a location-based entertainment business that includes theme park attractions, rides and exhibitions currently operating or planned in the U.S., UK, Europe, the Middle East and China, and its ground-breaking Atom Tickets partnership with Disney and Fox.\n\nIn a January 2014 story, \"A Star is Born\", chronicling Lionsgate's rise, ''[[The Economist]]'' proclaimed that \"Hollywood has a new star studio with a different approach to the film business\", reporting \"Lionsgate has achieved a level of success no one predicted.\"<ref>[https://www.economist.com/news/business/21595007-hollywood-has-new-star-studio-different-approach-film-business-fighting \"Hollywood Has A New Star Studio\"], economist.com; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Other==\nBurns was a co-founder and Chairman of Novica.com and a co-founder of the Hollywood Stock Exchange. A Republican, he is a contributing writer for ''The Huffington Post'' and ''Newsmax''.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/michael-burns/greenbacks-for-green-card_b_232134.html? \"Greenbacks for Green Cards\"], huffingtonpost.com; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref><ref>[http://www.newsmax.com/Newsfront/republican-party-changes-obama/2012/11/07/id/463294 Michael Burns: Ex Malo Bonum - From Bad Comes Good], newsmax.com; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref>\n\nHe is a member of the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts & Sciences]]. On December 11, 2014, he was elected as an independent director to the Board of Directors of [[Hasbro|Hasbro, Inc.]]<ref>[http://investor.hasbro.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=887244 Hasbro Elects Michael Burns to Board Of Directors], investor.hasbro.com; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref>\n\nHe also serves on the Leadership Council of global first responder International Medical Corps.{{cn|date=January 2020}} In March 2017 he was named Alumni of the Year by [[Arizona State University]].{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\n==Personal==\nBurns was married to actress [[Lori Loughlin]] from 1989 to 1996. He married actress [[Pell James]] in 2006.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/11/fashion/weddings/11JAME.html?_r=0 Pell James, Michael Burns wedding announcement], nytimes.com, June 11, 2006.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/michael-burns/ Huffington Post]\n*[http://www.lionsgate.com/corporate/governance/management/michael-burns/ Lionsgate Corporate Site Biography]\n*{{IMDb name|0122800|Michael Burns}}\n\n{{Lionsgate}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burns, Michael}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:California Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from New Canaan, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Arizona State University alumni]]\n[[Category:UCLA Anderson School of Management alumni]]\n[[Category:American investment bankers]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Catholics from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n", "name_user": "Lovemankind83", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Burns_(executive)"}
{"title_page": "Castle (TV series)", "text_new": "{{short description|American police procedural comedy-drama television series (2009-2016)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name          = Castle\n| image              = CastleIntertitle.png\n| genre              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Police procedural]]\n* [[Crime fiction|Crime]]\n* [[Comedy-drama]]\n}}\n| creator            = [[Andrew W. Marlowe]]\n| starring           = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Nathan Fillion]]\n* [[Stana Katic]] \n* [[Susan Sullivan]]\n* [[Ruben Santiago-Hudson]]\n* [[Molly Quinn]]\n* [[Jon Huertas]]\n* [[Tamala Jones]] \n* [[Seamus Dever]]\n* [[Penny Johnson Jerald]]\n* [[Toks Olagundoye]]\n}}\n| composer           = {{Plainlist| \n* [[Robert Duncan (composer)|Robert Duncan]]\n* [[Kim Planert]]\n}}\n| country            = United States\n| language           = English\n| num_seasons        = 8\n| num_episodes       = <onlyinclude>173</onlyinclude>\n| list_episodes      = List of Castle episodes\n| location           = [[Los Angeles]]\n| executive_producer = {{Plainlist|\n* Andrew W. Marlowe\n* [[Rob Bowman (director)|Rob Bowman]]\n* [[Armyan Bernstein]]\n* [[Laurie Zaks]]\n* Barry Schindel\n* [[Ren\u00e9 Echevarria]]\n* David Amann\n* David Grae\n* [[Rob Hanning]]\n* [[Terri Edda Miller]]\n* Terence Paul Winter\n* Alexi Hawley}}\n| camera             = [[Multi-camera setup|Multi-camera]]\n| runtime            = 43 minutes\n| company            = {{Plainlist|\n* [[ABC Studios]]\n* [[Beacon Pictures]]\n* Experimental Pictures<br>(2009\u20132013)<br>(seasons 2\u20135)\n* The Barry Schindel Company<br>(2009)<br>(season 1)\n* Milmar Pictures<br>(2013\u20132015)<br>(seasons 6\u20137)\n}}\n| distributor        = [[Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television]]\n| network            = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n| picture_format     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[High-definition television|HDTV]] [[1080i]]\n}}\n| audio_format       =\n| first_aired        = {{Start date|2009|3|9}}\n| last_aired         = {{End date|2016|5|16}}\n| website            = http://beta.abc.go.com/shows/castle\n}}\n\n'''''Castle''''' is<!--Do not change to \"was\", it still exists--> an American crime-[[comedy-drama]] television series,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mitovich |first1=Matt Webb |title=Castle's Nathan Fillion Talks Break-Up Twist: The Goal Is to Bring Back the Show 'Everybody Fell in Love With' |url=http://tvline.com/2015/10/10/castle-breakup-nathan-fillion-interview/ |publisher=[[TVLine]]}}</ref> which aired on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] for a total of eight seasons from March 9, 2009, to May 16, 2016. The series was produced jointly by [[Beacon Pictures]] and [[ABC Studios]]. \n\nCreated by [[Andrew W. Marlowe]], it primarily traces the lives of [[Richard Castle]] ([[Nathan Fillion]]), a best-selling mystery novelist, and [[Kate Beckett]] ([[Stana Katic]]), a homicide detective, as they solve various unusual crimes in [[New York City]]. Detective Beckett is initially infuriated at the thought of working with a writer and goes to great lengths to keep him out of her way. However, the two soon start developing feelings for each other. The overarching plot of the series focused on the romance between the two lead characters and their ongoing investigation of the murder of Beckett's mother. \n\nOn May 12, 2016, it was announced that despite some cast members signing one-year contracts for a potential ninth season, the show was canceled.<!--Per WP:CITELEAD, there is no need for a reference here-->\n\n==Premise==\n[[Richard Castle]] (Fillion) is a famous [[mystery (fiction)|mystery novelist]].  Bored and suffering from [[writer's block]], he kills off Derek Storm, the main character in his successful book series. He is brought in by the [[New York Police Department]] for questioning regarding a [[Copycat crimes|copy-cat murder]] based on one of his novels. He is intrigued by [[Kate Beckett]] (Katic), the detective assigned to the case. Castle is inspired to take Beckett as his [[muse]] for Nikki Heat, the main character of his next book series and uses his friendship with the mayor to force the police to let him shadow Beckett.  Castle's exuberant [[wikt:man child|man child]] personality clashes with Beckett's more reserved and professional demeanor.  However as Beckett begins to appreciate Castle's assistance in helping her catch killers, the two eventually become friends and then lovers.  Their cases often deal with murders occurring within various unusual subcultures or milieus, including reality TV shows, vampire enthusiasts, a science fiction convention, and a man who claims to be a time traveler.  A recurring plot line deals with the unsolved murder of Beckett's mother years before, an investigation which leads to an increasingly sprawling, and dangerous, conspiracy. The series also gives a just amount of screentime to the backstories of supporting characters like Javier Esposito, Kevin Ryan, Lanie Parish, Captain Roy Montgomery and Captain Gates, through multiple episodes.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n{{Main|List of Castle characters}}\n\n===Main===\n* [[Nathan Fillion]] as [[Richard Castle]], born Richard Alexander Rodgers, a best-selling mystery writer, who shadows and assists the NYPD. Castle is the only son of actress Martha Rodgers and a man known as Jackson Hunt, and also the father of Alexis Castle. He is the partner of Detective Kate Beckett. Castle's unusual theories sometimes irritate his coworkers, but often help solve the case. Richard has a complicated relationship with Detective Beckett. He is raising his daughter by himself, and his mother rents a room in his loft. \n* [[Stana Katic]] as [[Kate Beckett|Katherine \"Kate\" Beckett]], an NYPD homicide detective. Beckett is a daughter of Jim and Johanna Beckett. She was raised in Manhattan. She was inspired to be a detective, because of her mother\u2019s murder. She works with fellow detectives Javier Esposito and Kevin Ryan, and medical examiner Lanie Parish, who is her best friend. In the beginning Beckett's relationship with Castle was strained, but after a while Kate and Richard start to understand each other.\n* [[Jon Huertas]] as Detective [[Javier Esposito|Javier \"Javi\" Esposito]], a former [[United States Army Special Forces|Army Special Forces]] soldier who now works in the homicide division as part of Beckett's team. \n* [[Seamus Dever]] as Detective [[Kevin Ryan (Castle)|Kevin Ryan]], a former narcotics detective who works as part of Beckett's team. He is best friends with his partner, Detective Esposito. \n* [[Tamala Jones]] as [[Lanie Parish|Dr. Lanie Parish]], a medical examiner and a friend of Beckett and on-again-off-again love interest for Esposito.\n* [[Ruben Santiago-Hudson]] as [[Roy Montgomery (Castle)|Captain Roy Montgomery]] (seasons 1\u20133), Beckett's boss and captain of the 12th Precinct.\n* [[Molly Quinn]] as [[Alexis Castle]], Castle's daughter by his first wife, Meredith.\n* [[Susan Sullivan]] as [[Martha Rodgers]], Castle's mother, an actress on and off [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]].\n* [[Penny Johnson Jerald]] as [[Victoria Gates|Captain Victoria Gates]] (seasons 4\u20137), Captain Montgomery's replacement, formerly with [[Internal affairs (law enforcement)|Internal Affairs]].\n* [[Toks Olagundoye]] as Hayley Shipton (season 8), a quick-witted, free-spirited former [[Metropolitan Police Service|MPS]] cop and [[MI6]] operative from Britain who now works as a security specialist.\n\n===Recurring===\n* [[Arye Gross]] as [[List of Castle characters#Sidney Perlmutter|Dr. Sidney Perlmutter]], a medical examiner who assists on some of Beckett's cases and does little to hide his dislike of Castle\n* [[Scott Paulin]] as Jim Beckett, Kate Beckett's father\n* [[Maya Stojan]] as Tory Ellis, an NYPD Tech officer who assists on Beckett's cases\n* [[Juliana Dever]] as Jenny Ryan (n\u00e9e O'Malley), Ryan's wife\n* [[Darby Stanchfield]] as Meredith Harper, an actress who was Castle's first wife and Alexis's mother. She is regularly portrayed as self-centered and dramatic. \n* [[Monet Mazur]] as [[List of Castle characters#Gina Cowell|Gina Cowell]], Castle's publisher and second wife\n* [[Bailey Chase]] as Will Sorenson, an FBI agent and Beckett's ex-boyfriend\n* [[Michael Trucco]] as [[List of Castle characters#Detective Tom Demming|Detective Tom Demming]], a handsome robbery detective with whom Beckett briefly becomes involved\n* [[Victor Webster]] as [[List of Castle characters#Josh Davidson|Dr. Josh Davidson]], Beckett's motorcycle-riding, cardiac-surgeon ex-boyfriend\n* [[Michael Mosley (actor)|Michael Mosley]] as [[List of Castle characters#Jerry Tyson|Jerry Tyson/the Triple Killer (3XK)]], a methodical and meticulous serial killer who returns to New York every few years to terrorize the city. He is frequently believed to be dead, only to return again.\n* [[Jack Coleman (actor)|Jack Coleman]] as William Bracken, a popular, charismatic, and murderously corrupt US Senator representing the State of New York with ambitions of one day becoming president\n* [[Geoff Pierson]] as [[List of Castle characters#Mr. Smith|Mr. Smith]], a friend of Captain Montgomery's, who holds evidence that keeps the murderer of Beckett's mother away from her\n* [[Michael Dorn]] as Dr. Carver Burke, a psychiatrist who helps Beckett overcome her shooting and also deal with her various hidden emotions\n* [[Jonathan Adams (American actor)|Jonathan Adams]] as Vulcan Simmons, a ruthless Manhattan drug lord\n* [[Dan Castellaneta]] as Judge Markway, a judge who frequently issues warrants for Beckett, and one of Castle's poker buddies\n* [[Phil LaMarr]] as Dr. Holloway, a psychiatrist who evaluates the mental stability of suspects\n* [[Ken Baumann]] as Ashley, Alexis' steady boyfriend\n* Myko Olivier as Pi, Alexis's boyfriend (at the beginning of season six) with whom she shares an apartment for a while\n* [[Lisa Edelstein]] as Agent Rachel McCord, Beckett's partner during her brief time working for the Attorney-General's Office\n* [[Annie Wersching]] as Dr Kelly Nieman, a respected plastic surgeon with a secret life as Jerry Tyson's partner in crime\n* [[Matt Letscher]] as 'Henry Jenkins' (real name unknown), an impostor purportedly with the CIA who is involved with Castle's disappearance \n* [[Sunkrish Bala]] as Vikram Singh (season 8), a high-strung tech analyst with the Attorney General's office in Washington, D.C., where Beckett briefly works. He later works as a computer analyst for the NYPD. \n* [[Kristoffer Polaha]] as Caleb Brown, an idealistic public defender found to have links to the LokSat conspiracy. \n\nReal-life writers [[Stephen J. Cannell]], [[James Patterson]], [[Dennis Lehane]], and [[Michael Connelly]] appear as themselves during periodic games of poker at Castle's apartment. Typically, they discuss Castle and Beckett's current case and tease Castle about his involvement with Beckett. Following Cannell's death on September 30, 2010, an empty chair was kept at the poker table for a year in his honor.\n\n==Broadcast history==\n{{Main|List of Castle episodes}}\n''Castle'' premiered as a [[midseason replacement]] on ABC on March 9, 2009. ABC renewed ''Castle'' for a second season with an initial order of 13 episodes (later extended to 24 episodes).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118010177.html?categoryid=14&cs=1&ref=bd_tv |title=ABC gives full-season order to 'Castle' |first=Michael |last=Schneider |date=October 20, 2009 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=December 2, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118003771.html?categoryid=14&cs=1 |title=ABC's pilot pickup spree |first=Cynthia |last=Littleton |date=May 15, 2009 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref> The second season premiered on Monday, September 21, 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/FallTV-ABC-Premieres-1006734.aspx |title=ABC Announces Fall Premiere Dates for 19 Shows |first=Matt |last=Mitovich |date=June 9, 2009 |work=TVGuide.com |accessdate=June 9, 2009}}</ref> In March 2010, ABC renewed ''Castle'' for a third, 22-episode season, which began on September&nbsp;20, 2010.<ref name=\"ewseason3\">{{cite web |url=http://ausiellofiles.ew.com/2010/03/30/abc-renews-castle/ |title=ABC renews 'Castle' |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |date=March 30, 2010 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly|EW.com]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100401132516/http://ausiellofiles.ew.com/2010/03/30/abc-renews-castle/ |archivedate=April 1, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On November 11, 2010, ABC extended the episode order to 24.<ref name=\"4start\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2010/11/11/abc-orders-two-more-episodes-of-castle/71807|title=ABC orders two more episodes of Castle|work=TV by the Numbers|date=November 11, 2010|first=Bill|last=Gorman|accessdate=April 30, 2013}}</ref> On January 10, 2011, ABC announced ''Castle'' had been renewed for a fourth season for 22&nbsp;episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.monstersandcritics.com/smallscreen/news/article_1610769.php/ABC-and-ABC-Family-renew-Pretty-Little-Liars-Castle-Secret-Life-and-more |title=ABC and ABC Family renew Pretty Little Liars, Castle, Secret Life and more |work=[[Monsters and Critics]] |first=April |last=MacIntyre |date=January 10, 2011 |accessdate=April 30, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222214733/http://www.monstersandcritics.com/smallscreen/news/article_1610769.php/ABC-and-ABC-Family-renew-Pretty-Little-Liars-Castle-Secret-Life-and-more |archivedate=February 22, 2014 }}</ref> Season four premiered on September 19, 2011.<ref name=\"futon-s4\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/castle/listings |title=Episode Listings for Castle |publisher=The Futon Critic |accessdate=September 21, 2011}}</ref> On December 8, 2011, ABC ordered an additional episode bringing season 4 up to 23 episodes.<ref name=\"insidetv1\">{{cite web|last=Ross |first=Dalton |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/12/08/castle-scoop-abc-orders-additional-episode-exclusive/ |title='Castle' scoop: ABC orders additional episode \u2013 EXCLUSIVE |publisher=EW.com |date=December 8, 2011 |accessdate=2012-04-08}}</ref>\n\nOn May 10, 2012, ''Castle'' was renewed for a fifth season by ABC,<ref name=\"season5\">{{cite news|last=Hinckley |first=David | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/television/abc-renews-castle-revenge-grey-anatomy-modern-family-a-time-article-1.1076434/ |title=ABC renews 'Castle,' 'Revenge,' 'Grey's Anatomy,' 'Modern Family,' 'Once Upon a Time'|publisher=[[Mortimer Zuckerman]]|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|date=May 11, 2012| accessdate=2012-05-12}}</ref> which started on Monday September 24, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |last=Brown |first=Laurel |url=http://www.buddytv.com/articles/castle/abc-announces-its-fall-2012-pr-46746.aspx |title=ABC Announces Its Fall 2012 Premiere Dates: When Do 'Dancing with the Stars', 'Castle', 'Revenge' and More Return? |work=BuddyTV |date=July 26, 2012 |accessdate=2012-07-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730084155/http://www.buddytv.com/articles/castle/abc-announces-its-fall-2012-pr-46746.aspx |archive-date=July 30, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Two additional episodes were ordered on October 19, 2012, and February 5, 2013, respectively, which brought season 5 up to a total of 24 episodes.<ref>{{cite news |title=ABC Orders More 'Grey's Anatomy,' 'Modern Family,' 'Castle,' 'Middle' |first=Lesley |last=Goldberg |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/abc-orders-more-greys-anatomy-modern-family-middle-castle-381406 |newspaper=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=October 19, 2012 |accessdate=November 8, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2013/02/05/castle-additional-episode/ |title='Castle' scoop: ABC orders additional episode |magazine=Entertainment Weekly |date=February 5, 2013 |first=Sandra |last=Gonzalez |accessdate=April 30, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Bryant |first=Adam  | url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/Castle-Fifth-Season-Expanded-1060368.aspx |title=Scoop: Castle's Fifth Season Is Getting Bigger! \u2013 Today's News: Our Take |publisher= |work=[[TVGuide.com]] |date=February 5, 2013| accessdate=February 5, 2013}}</ref> On May 10, 2013, ABC announced via Twitter that ''Castle'' had been renewed for a sixth season.<ref name=\"s6renew\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ABC_Publicity/status/333013073961025536|title=#Castle #GreysAnatomy #Scandal have been renewed!|author=ABC Publicity|publisher=[[Twitter]]|date=May 10, 2013|accessdate=May 11, 2013}}</ref> On May 8, 2014, ABC renewed the series for a seventh season,<ref>{{cite web|last=Bricker|first=Tierney|title=ABC Renews Scandal, Grey's Anatomy, Revenge and 5 More Shows|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/527221/abc-renews-scandal-grey-s-anatomy-revenge-and-2-more-shows |publisher=E! News|date=May 8, 2014|accessdate=May 8, 2014}}</ref> which premiered on September 29, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hibberd|first=James|title=ABC fall premiere dates announced: 'Scandal' returns...|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2014/07/15/abc-premiere-dates/|publisher=Entertainment Weekly|date=July 15, 2014|accessdate=July 15, 2014}}</ref>  On May 7, 2015, the series was renewed for its eighth season,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2015/05/american-crime-castle-agents-of-shield-agent-carter-galavant-secrets-lies-fresh-off-the-boat-renewed-abc-1201422717/ |title=\u2018American Crime\u2019, \u2018Castle\u2019 \u2018S.H.I.E.L.D.\u2019, \u2018Agent Carter\u2019, \u2018Secrets & Lies\u2019, \u2018Galavant\u2019, \u2018Fresh Off the Boat\u2019 Among ABC Renewals |author=Andreeva, Nellie |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref> which premiered on September 21, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abc.go.com/shows/castle/news/castle-news/abc-announces-2015-2016-tv-season-8-premiere-date-fall-150610|title=Castle Season 8 Premiere Date Announced|work=ABC}}</ref> On April 18, 2016, ABC and ABC Productions announced that Stana Katic and Tamala Jones would not return for ''Castle''{{'}}s ninth season, should it be renewed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv/stana-katic-exits-det-kate-beckett-abc-castle-article-1.2605706|title=Stana Katic is out as Detective Kate Beckett on ABC\u2019s \u2018Castle\u2019|work=New York Daily News}}</ref> Despite several other cast members having signed on for a ninth season, on May 12, 2016, it was announced that the show would be cancelled instead; the final episode aired on May 16, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2016/05/12/castle-cancelled-season-9-beckett-stana-katic/|title=Castle Cancelled After 8 Seasons|work=[[TVLine]]|first=Michael|date=May 12, 2016|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|last=Ausiello|accessdate=May 12, 2016}}</ref>\n{{:List of Castle episodes}}\n\n==Reception==\n\n===U.S. Nielsen ratings===\n{{Television season ratings\n| hide_18_49_rank   = y\n| hide_18_49_rating = y\n\n| link1             = List of Castle episodes#Season 1 (2009)\n| timeslot1         = Monday 10:00 pm\n| timeslot_length1  = 8\n| episodes1         = 10\n| start1            = {{Start date|2009|3|9}}\n| end1              = {{End date|2009|5|11}}\n| startrating1      = 10.76<ref>{{cite web|last=Seidman |first=Robert |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/03/17/top-abc-primetime-shows-march-9-15-2009/14711/ |title=Top ABC Primetime Shows, March 9\u201315, 2009 \u2013 Ratings |publisher=TV by the Numbers|date=March 17, 2009 |accessdate=2012-04-08}}</ref>\n| endrating1        = 9.96<ref>{{cite web|first=Robert |last=Seidman |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/05/19/top-abc-primetime-shows-may-11-17-2009/19083/ |title=Top ABC Primetime Shows, May 11\u201317, 2009 \u2013 Ratings |publisher=TV by the Numbers|date=May 19, 2009 |accessdate=2012-04-08}}</ref>\n| season1           = 2008\u201309\n| rank1             = 41\n| viewers1          = 10.19<ref>{{