Jerald, Maya Stojan, Arye Gross: DVD & Blu-ray|website=www.amazon.co.uk}}</ref>\n| November 2, 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ezydvd.com.au/DVD/castle-season-8/dp/6176811|title=Castle - Season 8 DVD]|access-date=February 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204170024/http://www.ezydvd.com.au/DVD/castle-season-8/dp/6176811|archive-date=February 4, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| 22\n|5 \n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Cast commentary (Cool Boys episode), Cast and crew commentary (Heartbreaker episode), ''The Great Escape'' featurette based on The Blame Game episode, deleted scenes, and bloopers.\n|}\n\n===Syndication===\nIn June 2011, [[TNT (American TV network)|TNT]] acquired exclusive cable rights from [[Disney-ABC Domestic Television]] to air the first two seasons of ''Castle'' beginning in the summer of 2012.<ref name=\"tnt\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2011/06/08/tnt-acquires-hit-crime-drama-castle-243113/20110608tnt01/ |title=TNT Acquires Hit Crime Drama \"Castle\"|date=June 8, 2011 |work=The Futon Critic}}</ref> In advance of the series' fourth season, TNT broadcast an eight-hour marathon of episodes on September 15, 2011, including five from season 3.<ref name=\"season4\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/09/12/tnt-to-present-marathon-of-castle-episodes-as-hit-crime-drama-gears-up-to-launch-fourth-season-on-abc/103316/ |title=TNT to Present Marathon of 'Castle' Episodes as Hit Crime-Drama Gears Up to Launch Fourth Season on ABC|date=September 12, 2011 |first=Bill|last=Gorman|work=TV by the Numbers}}</ref>  ''Castle'' began airing on TNT every Wednesday beginning September 26, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.sitcomsonline.com/2012/08/tnt-fall-2012-schedule-with-castle.html |title=TNT Fall 2012 Schedule With Castle; Season 4 of Hot in Cleveland Begins Nov. 28 on TV Land With Special Guests Regis, Locklear, and More |work=SitcomsOnline.com |date=August 14, 2012 |accessdate=April 30, 2013}}</ref>  ''Castle'' also began airing in broadcast syndication on weekends beginning September 29, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.sitcomsonline.com/2012/01/natpe-2012-day-3-fall-2012-syndication.html |title=NATPE 2012: Day 3 - Fall 2012 Syndication; Nick at Nite Orders Telenovela Adaptation |work=SitcomsOnline.com |date=January 25, 2012 |accessdate=April 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Tie-in works===\n{{see also|Richard Castle#Literature}}\nIn the series, Castle writes a novel titled ''[[Heat Wave (novel)|Heat Wave]]''. As a tie-in, ABC and sister publisher [[Hachette Books#Hyperion Books|Hyperion Books]] released that novel as a real book with \"Richard Castle\" as the author. It is entirely in character from the dedication to the acknowledgments, although the latter mentions the principal cast and the show's creators by first name.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/castle-book-promote-series-86013 |title='Castle' book to promote series |first=James |last=Hibberd |date=June 30, 2009 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=January 6, 2010}}</ref> ABC released the first half of the novel in weekly increments on their website.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abc.go.com/shows/castle/books/3-heat-wave |title=Heat Wave - Richard Castle Books |publisher=[[American Broadcast Company|ABC]] |accessdate=December 2, 2009}}</ref> The complete novel was published in September 2009 as a hardcover, debuting at No. 26 on [[New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Best Seller list]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/18/books/bestseller/besthardfiction.html |title=Best Sellers: Hardcover Fiction |date=October 9, 2009 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=December 2, 2009}}</ref> In its fourth week on the list, ''Heat Wave'' broke into the top 10 at No. 6.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/08/books/bestseller/besthardfiction.html |title=Best Sellers: Hardcover Fiction |date=October 30, 2009 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=December 2, 2009}}</ref> ''Heat Wave'' was released in paperback on July 27, 2010, and debuted at No. 34 on ''The New York Times'' Best Seller Paperback Mass-Market list.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/15/books/bestseller/bestpapermassfiction.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=Best Sellers: Paperback Mass-Market Fiction |date=August 15, 2010 |accessdate=August 16, 2012}}</ref> It once again appeared on ''The New York Times'' Best Seller list on May 27, 2012, at No. 19.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2012-05-27/combined-print-and-e-book-fiction/list.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=Best Sellers: Combined Print & E-Book Fiction |date=May 27, 2012 |accessdate=August 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\n''Naked Heat'', the sequel to ''Heat Wave'', was released on September 28, 2010.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ausiello |first=Michael |url=http://ausiellofiles.ew.com/2010/03/17/castle-scoop-romance-castle-and-beckett/ |title='Castle' scoop: Romance for Castle and Beckett? |work=Inside TV |publisher=[[Entertainment Weekly|EW.com]] |date=March 17, 2010 |accessdate=May 24, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100322205528/http://ausiellofiles.ew.com/2010/03/17/castle-scoop-romance-castle-and-beckett/ |archivedate=March 22, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> ''Naked Heat'' debuted at No. 7 on ''The New York Times'' Best Seller list.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/17/books/bestseller/besthardfiction.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=Best Sellers: Hardcover Fiction |date=October 17, 2011 |accessdate=August 16, 2012}}</ref> As they did with ''Heat Wave'', ABC released a series of the early chapters online as a promotional tool.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abc.go.com/shows/castle/naked-heat |title=NAKED HEAT by Richard Castle |publisher=[[American Broadcast Company|ABC]] |date= |accessdate=August 16, 2012}}</ref> A third novel, titled ''Heat Rises'', was released on September 20, 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/Castle-ABC-Website-1031695.aspx |title=''Castle'' Exclusive: ABC Launches RichardCastle.Net |publisher=[[TV Guide|TVGuide.com]] |date=April 11, 2011 |accessdate=2012-04-08}}</ref> It debuted at No. 1 on ''The New York Times'' Best Seller list on October 9, 2011<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2011-10-09/hardcover-fiction/list.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=Best Sellers: Combined Print & E-Book Fiction |date=October 9, 2011 |accessdate=August 16, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Zamarripa |first=Shauna |url=https://tv.yahoo.com/news/castle-heat-rises-york-times-best-seller-195200005.html |title='Castle': Heat Rises is New York Times Best Seller |publisher=[[Yahoo!|Yahoo! TV]] |date=October 20, 2011 |accessdate=2012-04-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120710062545/http://tv.yahoo.com/news/castle-heat-rises-york-times-best-seller-195200005.html |archivedate=July 10, 2012 }}</ref> and at No. 5 on the ''[[USA TODAY]]'' Best-Selling Books list.<ref>{{cite news |title='Heat Rises' for Richard Castle's third thriller |first=Deirdre |last=Donahue |url=http://books.usatoday.com/bookbuzz/post/2011-09-29/heat-rises-for-richard-castles-third-thriller/549525/1 |work=[[USA Today]] |publisher=Book Buzz |date=September 29, 2011 |accessdate=August 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe season three finale introduced a [[graphic novel]] based on Castle's previous novel character, Derrick Storm. ''Castle: Richard Castle's Deadly Storm'' was published by [[Marvel Comics]] on September 28, 2011.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.majorspoilers.com/castle-television-show-gets-graphic-novel-treatment |title=Castle television show gets graphic novel treatment |publisher=Major Spoilers for [[Marvel Comics]] |date=May 16, 2011 |accessdate=2012-04-08}}</ref> It debuted at No. 3 on ''The New York Times'' Best Seller list on October 16, 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2011-10-16/hardcover-graphic-books/list.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=Best Sellers: Hardcover Graphic Books |date=October 12, 2011 |accessdate=August 16, 2012}}</ref> This has been followed by three more graphic novels, published a year apart. \n\nA fourth novel, titled ''Frozen Heat'', was released on September 11, 2012,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1401324444/ref=kinw_rke_tl_1 |title=Frozen Heat (Nikki Heat, Book 4) (9781401324445): Richard Castle: Books |publisher=Amazon.com |date=January 2, 2011 |accessdate=2012-04-08}}</ref> and debuted on ''The New York Times'' Best Seller list at No. 7 on September 23, 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2012-09-30/combined-print-and-e-book-fiction/list.html |title=Best Sellers - Combined Print & E-book Fiction |date=September 30, 2012 |accessdate=April 30, 2013 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> The fifth Nikki Heat novel ''[[Deadly Heat]]'' was released September 17, 2013 and debuted at No. 8 on ''The New York Times'' Best Seller list.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2013-10-06/combined-print-and-e-book-fiction/list.html |title=Best Sellers - Combined Print & E-book Fiction |date=October 6, 2013 |accessdate=October 10, 2013 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> ''Raging Heat'', the sixth novel, was released on September 16, 2014. It landed on No. 6 on ''The New York Times'' Hardcover Fiction Best Seller list<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2014/10/05/hardcover-fiction/|title=Hardcover Fiction Books - Best Sellers - October 5, 2014 - The New York Times|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> and on No. 17 on ''New York Times'' Combined Print and E-Book Fiction bestseller list<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2014/10/05/combined-print-and-e-book-fiction/|title=Combined Print & E-Book Fiction Books - Best Sellers - October 5, 2014 - The New York Times|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> on October 5, 2014. The seventh novel, ''Driving Heat'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2015/05/20/richard-castle-driving-heat-excerpt|title=Richard Castle's Driving Heat: Read an exclusive excerpt - EW.com|work=Entertainment Weekly's EW.com}}</ref> was released on September 15, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://castletv.net/release-date-for-nikki-heat-book-7/|title=Release Date for Nikki Heat Book #7|work=castletv.net|access-date=June 16, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110222627/http://castletv.net/release-date-for-nikki-heat-book-7|archive-date=January 10, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> It debuted on ''The New York Times'' Hardcover Fiction Best Seller list at No. 13<ref>{{cite web|title=Best Sellers \u2013 Hardcover Fiction|url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2015-10-04/hardcover-fiction/list.html|website=www.nytimes.com|accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref> on October 4, 2015.\n\nOn May 20, 2016, it was announced that two more novels would be published in the Nikki Heat series, even though the show itself had been canceled. The eighth book in the series, ''High Heat'', was published on October 25, 2016. The ninth, ''Heat Storm'', was released in May 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/bookmark/castle-book-series-lives-read-896199|title='Castle' Book Series Lives On (Read an Excerpt and See The Cover Now)|website=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2016-06-18}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018 a 10th Nikki Heat book was announced. ''Crashing Heat'' is due to be published by Kingswell, a division of Disney Books, on March 12, 2019, almost three years after the TV series ended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.disney.com/book/crashing-heat/|title=Crashing Heat by Richard Castle|website=books.disney.com|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, Hyperion announced three e-book novellas as part of Richard Castle's famous Derrick Storm series. The first novella of the series, ''A Brewing Storm'', was released in digital media on May 1, 2012. It debuted at No. 13 on ''The New York Times'' E-Book Fiction Best Seller list,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2012-05-20/e-book-fiction/list.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=Best Sellers: E-Book Fiction |date=May 20, 2012 |accessdate=August 16, 2012}}</ref> as well as No. 18 on ''The New York Times'' Combine Prints & E-book Fiction list<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2012-05-20/combined-print-and-e-book-fiction/list.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=Best Sellers: Combined Print & E-Book Fiction |date=May 20, 2012 |accessdate=August 16, 2012}}</ref> on May 20, 2012. On July 3, 2012, the second novella of the new Derrick Storm books, ''A Raging Storm'', was released in e-book format. It landed on ''The New York Times'' Best Seller e-books list at #19<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2012-07-22/e-book-fiction/list.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=Best Sellers: E-Book Fiction |date=July 22, 2012 |accessdate=August 16, 2012}}</ref> and at No. 31 for the combined Prints & E-book list, both on July 22, 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2012-07-22/combined-print-and-e-book-fiction/list.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=Best Sellers: Combined Print & E-Book Fiction |date=July 22, 2012 |accessdate=August 16, 2012}}</ref> The final Derrick Storm novella, ''A Bloody Storm'', was released on August 7, 2012. It debuted on ''The New York Times'' Best Seller e-books list at #20<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/e-book-fiction/list.html |title=Best Sellers - E-book Fiction |date=May 5, 2013 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=April 30, 2013}}</ref> and at #34<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2012-08-26/combined-print-and-e-book-fiction/list.html |title=Best Sellers - Combined Print & E-book Fiction |date=August 26, 2012 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=April 30, 2013}}</ref> on the combined Prints & E-book list on August 26, 2012.\n\n===Video game===\n''Castle: Never Judge a Book by its Cover'' was released on July 9, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Castle: Never Judge a Book by its Cover|url=http://store.steampowered.com/app/301740/Castle_Never_Judge_a_Book_by_its_Cover/|website=Steam|accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref> The game is available on [[Steam (software)|Steam]] and can be downloaded on most mobile devices.<ref name=game>{{cite web|last1=Curiel|first1=Rose|title=Castle: Never Judge a Book by Its Cover Game Lets You Solve Crime with Caskett|url=http://abc.go.com/shows/castle/news/castle-news/150114-castle-game-never-judge-a-book-by-its-cover|website=ABC|accessdate=24 January 2018|date=January 20, 2015}}</ref> Players work with Castle and Beckett to [[hidden object game|find clues]] and stop a serial killer.<ref name=game />\n\n===Derrick Storm television series===\nOn August 20, 2014, ABC announced that the early development stage had begun on a television series centered on Derrick Storm. The series was to have been a CIA procedural written by [[Gregory Poirier]], who was to have executive-produced it with ''Castle''{{'}}s Andrew Marlowe and Terri Miller.<ref>{{cite news |last=Abrams |first=Natalie |date=August 20, 2014 |title=ABC developing drama based on Derrick Storm novels from 'Castle' |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2014/08/20/abc-castle-derrick-storm |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=June 16, 2016}}</ref> There were no subsequent announcements about a Derrick Storm TV series, indicating that development had concluded.\n\n== See also ==\n* ''[[The Rookie (TV series)|The Rookie]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist\n| colwidth = 30em\n| refs =\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|Castle (TV series)}}\n* {{Official website|1=http://beta.abc.go.com/shows/castle}}\n* {{IMDb title|1219024|Castle}}\n* {{tv.com show|castle|Castle}}\n* {{TV Guide show|296087|Castle}}\n* {{tvbtn|castle-ratings|Castle}}\n\n{{Castle (TV series)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Castle}}\n[[Category:Castle (TV series)| ]]\n[[Category:2009 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2016 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:2000s American comedy-drama television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American crime drama television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American mystery television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American police comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American comedy-drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American crime drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American mystery television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American police comedy television series]]\n[[Category:American Broadcasting Company original programming]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Fictional portrayals of the New York City Police Department]]\n[[Category:Television series by ABC Studios]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Television shows about writers]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in New York City]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American police procedural comedy-drama television series (2009-2016)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name          = Castle\n| image              = CastleIntertitle.png\n| genre              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Police procedural]]\n* [[Crime fiction|Crime]]\n* [[Comedy-drama]]\n}}\n| creator            = [[Andrew W. Marlowe]]\n| starring           = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Nathan Fillion]]\n* [[Stana Katic]] \n* [[Susan Sullivan]]\n* [[Ruben Santiago-Hudson]]\n* [[Molly Quinn]]\n* [[Jon Huertas]]\n* [[Tamala Jones]] \n* [[Seamus Dever]]\n* [[Penny Johnson Jerald]]\n* [[Toks Olagundoye]]\n}}\n| composer           = {{Plainlist| \n* [[Robert Duncan (composer)|Robert Duncan]]\n* [[Kim Planert]]\n}}\n| country            = United States\n| language           = English\n| num_seasons        = 8\n| num_episodes       = <onlyinclude>173</onlyinclude>\n| list_episodes      = List of Castle episodes\n| location           = [[Los Angeles]]\n| executive_producer = {{Plainlist|\n* Andrew W. Marlowe\n* [[Rob Bowman (director)|Rob Bowman]]\n* [[Armyan Bernstein]]\n* [[Laurie Zaks]]\n* Barry Schindel\n* [[Ren\u00e9 Echevarria]]\n* David Amann\n* David Grae\n* [[Rob Hanning]]\n* [[Terri Edda Miller]]\n* Terence Paul Winter\n* Alexi Hawley}}\n| camera             = [[Multi-camera setup|Multi-camera]]\n| runtime            = 43 minutes\n| company            = {{Plainlist|\n* [[ABC Studios]]\n* [[Beacon Pictures]]\n* Experimental Pictures<br>(2009\u20132013)<br>(seasons 2\u20135)\n* The Barry Schindel Company<br>(2009)<br>(season 1)\n* Milmar Pictures<br>(2013\u20132015)<br>(seasons 6\u20137)\n}}\n| distributor        = [[Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television]]\n| network            = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n| picture_format     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[High-definition television|HDTV]] [[1080i]]\n}}\n| audio_format       =\n| first_aired        = {{Start date|2009|3|9}}\n| last_aired         = {{End date|2016|5|16}}\n| website            = http://beta.abc.go.com/shows/castle\n}}\n\n'''''Castle''''' is<!--Do not change to \"was\", it still exists--> an American crime-[[comedy-drama]] television series,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mitovich |first1=Matt Webb |title=Castle's Nathan Fillion Talks Break-Up Twist: The Goal Is to Bring Back the Show 'Everybody Fell in Love With' |url=http://tvline.com/2015/10/10/castle-breakup-nathan-fillion-interview/ |publisher=[[TVLine]]}}</ref> which aired on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] for a total of eight seasons from March 9, 2009, to May 16, 2016. The series was produced jointly by [[Beacon Pictures]] and [[ABC Studios]]. \n\nCreated by [[Andrew W. Marlowe]], it primarily traces the lives of [[Richard Castle]] ([[Nathan Fillion]]), a best-selling mystery novelist, and [[Kate Beckett]] ([[Stana Katic]]), a homicide detective, as they solve various unusual crimes in [[New York City]]. Detective Beckett is initially infuriated at the thought of working with a writer and goes to great lengths to keep him out of her way. However, the two soon start developing feelings for each other. The overarching plot of the series focused on the romance between the two lead characters and their ongoing investigation of the murder of Beckett's mother. \n\nOn May 12, 2016, it was announced that despite some cast members signing one-year contracts for a potential ninth season, the show was canceled.<!--Per WP:CITELEAD, there is no need for a reference here-->\n\n==Premise==\n[[Richard Castle]] (Fillion) is a famous [[mystery (fiction)|mystery novelist]].  Bored and suffering from [[writer's block]], he kills off Derek Storm, the main character in his successful book series. He is brought in by the [[New York Police Department]] for questioning regarding a [[Copycat crimes|copy-cat murder]] based on one of his novels. He is intrigued by [[Kate Beckett]] (Katic), the detective assigned to the case. Castle is inspired to take Beckett as his [[muse]] for Nikki Heat, the main character of his next book series and uses his friendship with the mayor to force the police to let him shadow Beckett.  Castle's exuberant [[wikt:man child|man child]] personality clashes with Beckett's more reserved and professional demeanor.  However as Beckett begins to appreciate Castle's assistance in helping her catch killers, the two eventually become friends and then lovers.  Their cases often deal with murders occurring within various unusual subcultures or milieus, including reality TV shows, vampire enthusiasts, a science fiction convention, and a man who claims to be a time traveler.  A recurring plot line deals with the unsolved murder of Beckett's mother years before, an investigation which leads to an increasingly sprawling, and dangerous, conspiracy. The series also gives a just amount of screentime to the backstories of supporting characters like Javier Esposito, Kevin Ryan, Lanie Parish, Captain Roy Montgomery and Captain Gates, through multiple episodes.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n{{Main|List of Castle characters}}\n\n===Main===\n* [[Nathan Fillion]] as [[Richard Castle]], born Richard Alexander Rodgers, a best-selling mystery writer, who shadows and assists the NYPD. Castle is the only son of actress Martha Rodgers and a man known as Jackson Hunt, and also the father of Alexis Castle. He is the partner of Detective Kate Beckett. Castle's unusual theories sometimes irritate his coworkers, but often help solve the case. Richard has a complicated relationship with Detective Beckett. He is raising his daughter by himself, and his mother rents a room in his loft. \n* [[Stana Katic]] as [[Kate Beckett|Katherine \"Kate\" Beckett]], an NYPD homicide detective. Beckett is a daughter of Jim and Johanna Beckett. She was raised in Manhattan. She was inspired to be a detective, because of her mother\u2019s murder. She works with fellow detectives Javier Esposito and Kevin Ryan, and medical examiner Lanie Parish, who is her best friend. In the beginning Beckett's relationship with Castle was strained, but after a while Kate and Richard start to understand each other.\n* [[Jon Huertas]] as Detective [[Javier Esposito|Javier \"Javi\" Esposito]], a former [[United States Army Special Forces|Army Special Forces]] soldier who now works in the homicide division as part of Beckett's team. \n* [[Seamus Dever]] as Detective [[Kevin Ryan (Castle)|Kevin Ryan]], a former narcotics detective who works as part of Beckett's team. He is best friends with his partner, Detective Esposito. \n* [[Tamala Jones]] as [[Lanie Parish|Dr. Lanie Parish]], a medical examiner and a friend of Beckett and on-again-off-again love interest for Esposito.\n* [[Ruben Santiago-Hudson]] as [[Roy Montgomery (Castle)|Captain Roy Montgomery]] (seasons 1\u20133), Beckett's boss and captain of the 12th Precinct.\n* [[Molly Quinn]] as [[Alexis Castle]], Castle's daughter by his first wife, Meredith.\n* [[Susan Sullivan]] as [[Martha Rodgers]], Castle's mother, an actress on and off [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]].\n* [[Penny Johnson Jerald]] as [[Victoria Gates|Captain Victoria Gates]] (seasons 4\u20137), Captain Montgomery's replacement, formerly with [[Internal affairs (law enforcement)|Internal Affairs]].\n* [[Toks Olagundoye]] as Hayley Shipton (season 8), a quick-witted, free-spirited former [[Metropolitan Police Service|MPS]] cop and [[MI6]] operative from Britain who now works as a security specialist.\n\n===Recurring===\n* [[Arye Gross]] as [[List of Castle characters#Sidney Perlmutter|Dr. Sidney Perlmutter]], a medical examiner who assists on some of Beckett's cases and does little to hide his dislike of Castle\n* [[Scott Paulin]] as Jim Beckett, Kate Beckett's father\n* [[Maya Stojan]] as Tory Ellis, an NYPD Tech officer who assists on Beckett's cases\n* [[Juliana Dever]] as Jenny Ryan (n\u00e9e O'Malley), Ryan's wife\n* [[Darby Stanchfield]] as Meredith Harper, an actress who was Castle's first wife and Alexis's mother. She is regularly portrayed as self-centered and dramatic. \n* [[Monet Mazur]] as [[List of Castle characters#Gina Cowell|Gina Cowell]], Castle's publisher and second wife\n* [[Bailey Chase]] as Will Sorenson, an FBI agent and Beckett's ex-boyfriend\n* [[Michael Trucco]] as [[List of Castle characters#Detective Tom Demming|Detective Tom Demming]], a handsome robbery detective with whom Beckett briefly becomes involved\n* [[Victor Webster]] as [[List of Castle characters#Josh Davidson|Dr. Josh Davidson]], Beckett's motorcycle-riding, cardiac-surgeon ex-boyfriend\n* [[Michael Mosley (actor)|Michael Mosley]] as [[List of Castle characters#Jerry Tyson|Jerry Tyson/the Triple Killer (3XK)]], a methodical and meticulous serial killer who returns to New York every few years to terrorize the city. He is frequently believed to be dead, only to return again.\n* [[Jack Coleman (actor)|Jack Coleman]] as William Bracken, a popular, charismatic, and murderously corrupt US Senator representing the State of New York with ambitions of one day becoming president\n* [[Geoff Pierson]] as [[List of Castle characters#Mr. Smith|Mr. Smith]], a friend of Captain Montgomery's, who holds evidence that keeps the murderer of Beckett's mother away from her\n* [[Michael Dorn]] as Dr. Carver Burke, a psychiatrist who helps Beckett overcome her shooting and also deal with her various hidden emotions\n* [[Jonathan Adams (American actor)|Jonathan Adams]] as Vulcan Simmons, a ruthless Manhattan drug lord\n* [[Dan Castellaneta]] as Judge Markway, a judge who frequently issues warrants for Beckett, and one of Castle's poker buddies\n* [[Phil LaMarr]] as Dr. Holloway, a psychiatrist who evaluates the mental stability of suspects\n* [[Ken Baumann]] as Ashley, Alexis' steady boyfriend\n* Myko Olivier as Pi, Alexis's boyfriend (at the beginning of season six) with whom she shares an apartment for a while\n* [[Lisa Edelstein]] as Agent Rachel McCord, Beckett's partner during her brief time working for the Attorney-General's Office\n* [[Annie Wersching]] as Dr Kelly Nieman, a respected plastic surgeon with a secret life as Jerry Tyson's partner in crime\n* [[Matt Letscher]] as 'Henry Jenkins' (real name unknown), an impostor purportedly with the CIA who is involved with Castle's disappearance \n* [[Sunkrish Bala]] as Vikram Singh (season 8), a high-strung tech analyst with the Attorney General's office in Washington, D.C., where Beckett briefly works. He later works as a computer analyst for the NYPD. \n* [[Kristoffer Polaha]] as Caleb Brown, an idealistic public defender found to have links to the LokSat conspiracy. \n\nReal-life writers [[Stephen J. Cannell]], [[James Patterson]], [[Dennis Lehane]], and [[Michael Connelly]] appear as themselves during periodic games of poker at Castle's apartment. Typically, they discuss Castle and Beckett's current case and tease Castle about his involvement with Beckett. Following Cannell's death on September 30, 2010, an empty chair was kept at the poker table for a year in his honor.\n\n==Broadcast history==\n{{Main|List of Castle episodes}}\n''Castle'' premiered as a [[midseason replacement]] on ABC on March 9, 2009. ABC renewed ''Castle'' for a second season with an initial order of 13 episodes (later extended to 24 episodes).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118010177.html?categoryid=14&cs=1&ref=bd_tv |title=ABC gives full-season order to 'Castle' |first=Michael |last=Schneider |date=October 20, 2009 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=December 2, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118003771.html?categoryid=14&cs=1 |title=ABC's pilot pickup spree |first=Cynthia |last=Littleton |date=May 15, 2009 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref> The second season premiered on Monday, September 21, 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/FallTV-ABC-Premieres-1006734.aspx |title=ABC Announces Fall Premiere Dates for 19 Shows |first=Matt |last=Mitovich |date=June 9, 2009 |work=TVGuide.com |accessdate=June 9, 2009}}</ref> In March 2010, ABC renewed ''Castle'' for a third, 22-episode season, which began on September&nbsp;20, 2010.<ref name=\"ewseason3\">{{cite web |url=http://ausiellofiles.ew.com/2010/03/30/abc-renews-castle/ |title=ABC renews 'Castle' |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |date=March 30, 2010 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly|EW.com]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100401132516/http://ausiellofiles.ew.com/2010/03/30/abc-renews-castle/ |archivedate=April 1, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On November 11, 2010, ABC extended the episode order to 24.<ref name=\"4start\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2010/11/11/abc-orders-two-more-episodes-of-castle/71807|title=ABC orders two more episodes of Castle|work=TV by the Numbers|date=November 11, 2010|first=Bill|last=Gorman|accessdate=April 30, 2013}}</ref> On January 10, 2011, ABC announced ''Castle'' had been renewed for a fourth season for 22&nbsp;episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.monstersandcritics.com/smallscreen/news/article_1610769.php/ABC-and-ABC-Family-renew-Pretty-Little-Liars-Castle-Secret-Life-and-more |title=ABC and ABC Family renew Pretty Little Liars, Castle, Secret Life and more |work=[[Monsters and Critics]] |first=April |last=MacIntyre |date=January 10, 2011 |accessdate=April 30, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222214733/http://www.monstersandcritics.com/smallscreen/news/article_1610769.php/ABC-and-ABC-Family-renew-Pretty-Little-Liars-Castle-Secret-Life-and-more |archivedate=February 22, 2014 }}</ref> Season four premiered on September 19, 2011.<ref name=\"futon-s4\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/castle/listings |title=Episode Listings for Castle |publisher=The Futon Critic |accessdate=September 21, 2011}}</ref> On December 8, 2011, ABC ordered an additional episode bringing season 4 up to 23 episodes.<ref name=\"insidetv1\">{{cite web|last=Ross |first=Dalton |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/12/08/castle-scoop-abc-orders-additional-episode-exclusive/ |title='Castle' scoop: ABC orders additional episode \u2013 EXCLUSIVE |publisher=EW.com |date=December 8, 2011 |accessdate=2012-04-08}}</ref>\n\nOn May 10, 2012, ''Castle'' was renewed for a fifth season by ABC,<ref name=\"season5\">{{cite news|last=Hinckley |first=David | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/television/abc-renews-castle-revenge-grey-anatomy-modern-family-a-time-article-1.1076434/ |title=ABC renews 'Castle,' 'Revenge,' 'Grey's Anatomy,' 'Modern Family,' 'Once Upon a Time'|publisher=[[Mortimer Zuckerman]]|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|date=May 11, 2012| accessdate=2012-05-12}}</ref> which started on Monday September 24, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |last=Brown |first=Laurel |url=http://www.buddytv.com/articles/castle/abc-announces-its-fall-2012-pr-46746.aspx |title=ABC Announces Its Fall 2012 Premiere Dates: When Do 'Dancing with the Stars', 'Castle', 'Revenge' and More Return? |work=BuddyTV |date=July 26, 2012 |accessdate=2012-07-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730084155/http://www.buddytv.com/articles/castle/abc-announces-its-fall-2012-pr-46746.aspx |archive-date=July 30, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Two additional episodes were ordered on October 19, 2012, and February 5, 2013, respectively, which brought season 5 up to a total of 24 episodes.<ref>{{cite news |title=ABC Orders More 'Grey's Anatomy,' 'Modern Family,' 'Castle,' 'Middle' |first=Lesley |last=Goldberg |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/abc-orders-more-greys-anatomy-modern-family-middle-castle-381406 |newspaper=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=October 19, 2012 |accessdate=November 8, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2013/02/05/castle-additional-episode/ |title='Castle' scoop: ABC orders additional episode |magazine=Entertainment Weekly |date=February 5, 2013 |first=Sandra |last=Gonzalez |accessdate=April 30, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Bryant |first=Adam  | url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/Castle-Fifth-Season-Expanded-1060368.aspx |title=Scoop: Castle's Fifth Season Is Getting Bigger! \u2013 Today's News: Our Take |publisher= |work=[[TVGuide.com]] |date=February 5, 2013| accessdate=February 5, 2013}}</ref> On May 10, 2013, ABC announced via Twitter that ''Castle'' had been renewed for a sixth season.<ref name=\"s6renew\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ABC_Publicity/status/333013073961025536|title=#Castle #GreysAnatomy #Scandal have been renewed!|author=ABC Publicity|publisher=[[Twitter]]|date=May 10, 2013|accessdate=May 11, 2013}}</ref> On May 8, 2014, ABC renewed the series for a seventh season,<ref>{{cite web|last=Bricker|first=Tierney|title=ABC Renews Scandal, Grey's Anatomy, Revenge and 5 More Shows|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/527221/abc-renews-scandal-grey-s-anatomy-revenge-and-2-more-shows |publisher=E! News|date=May 8, 2014|accessdate=May 8, 2014}}</ref> which premiered on September 29, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hibberd|first=James|title=ABC fall premiere dates announced: 'Scandal' returns...|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2014/07/15/abc-premiere-dates/|publisher=Entertainment Weekly|date=July 15, 2014|accessdate=July 15, 2014}}</ref>  On May 7, 2015, the series was renewed for its eighth season,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2015/05/american-crime-castle-agents-of-shield-agent-carter-galavant-secrets-lies-fresh-off-the-boat-renewed-abc-1201422717/ |title=\u2018American Crime\u2019, \u2018Castle\u2019 \u2018S.H.I.E.L.D.\u2019, \u2018Agent Carter\u2019, \u2018Secrets & Lies\u2019, \u2018Galavant\u2019, \u2018Fresh Off the Boat\u2019 Among ABC Renewals |author=Andreeva, Nellie |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref> which premiered on September 21, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abc.go.com/shows/castle/news/castle-news/abc-announces-2015-2016-tv-season-8-premiere-date-fall-150610|title=Castle Season 8 Premiere Date Announced|work=ABC}}</ref> On April 18, 2016, ABC and ABC Productions announced that Stana Katic and Tamala Jones would not return for ''Castle''{{'}}s ninth season, should it be renewed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv/stana-katic-exits-det-kate-beckett-abc-castle-article-1.2605706|title=Stana Katic is out as Detective Kate Beckett on ABC\u2019s \u2018Castle\u2019|work=New York Daily News}}</ref> Despite several other cast members having signed on for a ninth season, on May 12, 2016, it was announced that the show would be cancelled instead; the final episode aired on May 16, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2016/05/12/castle-cancelled-season-9-beckett-stana-katic/|title=Castle Cancelled After 8 Seasons|work=[[TVLine]]|first=Michael|date=May 12, 2016|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|last=Ausiello|accessdate=May 12, 2016}}</ref>\n{{:List of Castle episodes}}\n\n==Reception==\n\n===U.S. Nielsen ratings===\n{{Television season ratings\n| hide_18_49_rank   = y\n| hide_18_49_rating = y\n\n| link1             = List of Castle episodes#Season 1 (2009)\n| timeslot1         = Monday 10:00 pm\n| timeslot_length1  = 8\n| episodes1         = 10\n| start1            = {{Start date|2009|3|9}}\n| end1              = {{End date|2009|5|11}}\n| startrating1         = 10.76<ref>{{cite web|last=Seidman |first=Robert |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/03/17/top-abc-primetime-shows-march-9-15-2009/14711/ |title=Top ABC Primetime Shows, March 9\u201315, 2009 \u2013 Ratings |publisher=TV by the Numbers|date=March 17, 2009 |accessdate=2012-04-08}}</ref>\n| endrating1           = 9.96<ref>{{cite web|first=Robert |last=Seidman |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/05/19/top-abc-primetime-shows-may-11-17-2009/19083/ |title=Top ABC Primetime Shows, May 11\u201317, 2009 \u2013 Ratings |publisher=TV by the Numbers|date=May 19, 2009 |accessdate=2012-04-08}}</ref>\n| season1           = 2008\u201309\n| rank1             = 41\n| viewers1          = 10.19<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=051909_05 |title=ABC Medianet |publisher=ABC Medianet |date=May 19, 2009 |accessdate=2012-04-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314121838/http://abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=051909_05 |archivedate=March 14, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n| link2             = List of Castle episodes#Season 2 (2009\u201310)\n| episodes2         = 24\n| start2            = {{Start date|2009|9|21}}\n| end2              = {{End date|2010|5|17}}\n| startrating2         = 9.26<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/09/22/monday-broadcast-final-numbers/28114/ |title=Monday broadcast final numbers \u2013 Ratings |publisher=TV by the Numbers|date= |accessdate=2012-04-08}}</ref>\n| endrating2           = 10.07<ref>{{cite web|last=Calabria |first=Rosario T. |url=http://yourentertainmentnow.com/2011/05/17/broadcast-